]|access-date=28 November 2019|date=7 November 2019|first1=Christie|last1=K}}</ref>\n| leadfigures1 = ''Non-centralized leadership''\n| leadfigures2 = {{flagicon|Lebanon}} [[Michel Aoun]]<br />{{flagicon|Lebanon}} [[Nabih Berri]]<br />{{flagicon|Lebanon}} [[Hassan Diab (minister)|Hassan Diab]]<br />{{flagicon|Lebanon}} [[Saad Hariri]] (17\u201329 Oct)<br />{{flagicon|Hezbollah}} [[Hassan Nasrallah]]<br /> [[Gebran Bassil]] <br />{{flagicon image|Flag_of_the_Progressive_Socialist_Party.svg}} [[Walid Jumblatt]]<br />{{flagicon image|Flag_of_the_Syrian_Social_Nationalist_Party.svg}} Fares al-Saad<br />{{flagicon image|Flag_of_the_Lebanese_Democratic_Party.svg}} [[Talal Arslan]]<br /> [[Suleiman Frangieh, Jr.]]<br />{{flagicon image|600px solid HEX-990066.svg}} [[Najib Mikati]]<br />{{flagicon image|Armenian Revolutionary Federation Flag.svg}} [[Hagop Pakradounian]]\n| arrests       = 70 (released the next day due to lack of reason for arrest)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indopremier.com/ipotnews/newsDetail.php?jdl=Tens_of_thousands_protest_in_Lebanon_for_third_day&news_id=1452420&group_news=ALLNEWS&news_date=&taging_subtype=LEBANON&name=&search=y_general&q=LEBANON,%20&halaman=1|title=Tens of thousands protest in Lebanon for third day|last=SECURITIES|first=PT INDO PREMIER|date=20 October 2019|website=IPOTNEWS|language=id|access-date=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n| casualties1    = At least 7 killed and 540 injured as of 19 January 2020<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=25209&LangID=E | title=OHCHR &#124; Press briefing note on Lebanon}}</ref><ref name=\"An-Nahar\">{{cite news|title=\u0639\u0636\u0648 \u0628\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0648\u064a\u0641\u0627\u062a \u0639\u0644\u0627\u0621 \u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0641\u062e\u0631 \u064a\u0633\u0642\u0637 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0635\u0627\u0635 \u062a\u062d\u062a \u062c\u0633\u0631 \u062e\u0644\u062f\u0629|url=https://www.annahar.com/article/1067073-\u0639\u0636\u0648-\u0641\u064a-\u0628\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0648\u064a\u0641\u0627\u062a-\u064a\u0635\u0627\u0628-\u0628\u0637\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062a-\u0646\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629-\u0646\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0629-\u062a\u062d\u062a-\u062c\u0633\u0631-\u062e\u0627\u062f\u0629-\u0648\u064a\u0646\u0642\u0644-\u0627\u0644\u0649-\u0645\u0633\u062a\u0634\u0641\u0649-\u0643\u0645\u0627\u0644|access-date=12 November 2019|publisher=[[An-Nahar]]}}</ref><ref name=\"dailystar.com.lb\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-25/496220-two-die-in-car-crash-after-hitting-roadblock-in-jiyyeh.ashx|title=Anger breaks out after two die in roadblock crash|date=25 November 2019|access-date=26 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref name=\"540injured\" />\n| casualties2   = 142 police injured as of 19 January 2020 \n| concessions   = Resignation of [[Prime Minister of Lebanon|Prime Minister]] [[Saad Hariri]]\n| sidebox       = \n| campaignbox   = {{Campaignbox 2018\u201319 Arab protests}}{{Campaignbox Lebanon conflicts}}\n}}\n\nCivil protests are taking place in [[Lebanon]], initially triggered by planned taxes on gasoline, tobacco and [[VoIP]] calls on applications such as [[WhatsApp]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-17/493723-lebanon-to-charge-6-on-whatsapp-call-report.ashx|title=Lebanese govt to charge USD 0.20 a day for WhatsApp calls|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=18 October 2019|date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/protests-erupt-lebanon-plans-impose-taxes-191017194856354.html|title=Protests erupt in Lebanon over plans to impose new taxes|website=aljazeera.com|access-date=18 October 2019|date=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/lebanon-whatsapp-tax-sparks-mass-protests/a-50880357|title=Lebanon: WhatsApp tax sparks mass protests|date=10 October 2019|publisher=Deutsche Welle|website=DW|language=en-GB|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> but quickly expanding into a country-wide condemnation of [[sectarian]] rule,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://reportsyndication.news.blog/2019/10/27/lebanon-protesters-find-strength-in-unity-ditched-sectarianism/|title=Lebanon Protesters Found Strength in Unity, Ditched Sectarianism|last=|first=|date=27 October 2019|website=Report Syndication|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> stagnant economy, unemployment, endemic corruption in the public sector,<ref name=\":2\" /> legislation that is perceived to shield the ruling class from accountability (such as banking secrecy)<ref>{{cite news |title=Protesters march from Al Nour Square to Central Bank in Tripoli |url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/News/Local/979920/Protesters_march_from_Al_Nour_Square_to_Central_Bank_in_Tripoli |access-date=26 October 2019 |work=MTV Lebanon |date=22 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Protesters block Karakoul Druze-Mar Elias road |url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/News/Local/979923/Protesters_block_Karakoul_Druze-Mar_Elias_road |access-date=26 October 2019 |work=MTV Lebanon |date=22 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and failures of the government to provide basic services such as electricity, water and sanitation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-17/whatsapp-protests-erupt-in-lebanon-as-economic-crisis-deepens|title=Nationwide Protests Erupt in Lebanon as Economic Crisis Deepens|last=Khraiche|first=Dana|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]|archive-date=|access-date=18 October 2019|date=17 October 2019}}</ref> The protests first erupted on 17 October 2019. It has been 144 days since they have started.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/lebanese-protesters-close-roads-over-imposition-of-new-taxes/2019/10/17/d2f4482a-f116-11e9-bb7e-d2026ee0c199_story.html|title=Protests spread across Lebanon over proposed new taxes|agency=AP|author=Fadi Tawil|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019|date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-18/493775-protests-erupt-over-taxes-as-govt-races-to-wrap-up-budget.ashx|title=Protests erupt over taxes as govt races to wrap up budget|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=18 October 2019|date=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50095448|title=Lebanon scraps WhatsApp tax as protests rage|date=18 October 2019|access-date=18 October 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the protests, Lebanon entered a political crisis, with Prime Minister [[Saad Hariri]] tendering his resignation and echoing protesters' demands for a government of independent specialists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the961.com/news/lebanese-protesters-addressed-president-aoun-with-an-urgent-demand/|title=Lebanese Protesters Addressed President Aoun with an Urgent Demand/|last=The961|first=News|date=1 November 2019|website=the961.com|language=en-EN|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref> Other politicians targeted by the protests have remained in power. On 19 December 2019, former Minister of Education [[Hassan Diab (minister)|Hassan Diab]] was designated the next prime minister and tasked with forming a new cabinet.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50851319|title=Lebanon protests: University professor Hassan Diab nominated to be PM|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> Protests and acts of [[civil disobedience]] have since continued, with protesters denouncing and condemning the designation of Diab as prime minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/hezbollah-backed-hassan-diab-lebanon-pm-191219155153401.html|title=Lebanese president asks Hassan Diab to form government|date=19 December 2019|access-date=2 January 2020|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/roadblocks-lebanon-anger-rises-diab-pick-pm-191220091929392.html|title=Roadblocks across Lebanon as anger rises over Diab pick as PM|date=20 December 2019|access-date=2 January 2020|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-31/498331-day-76-new-years-revolution.ashx|date=31 December 2019|access-date=2 January 2020|title=Day 76: New Year's Revolution|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> On 22 January, Lebanon named Hassan Diab as its prime minister to lead the new cabinet of 20 members, after three months of mass protests. Diab was appointed with the support of [[Hezbollah]], its allies, and the [[Free Patriotic Movement]] led by [[Gebran Bassil]].<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.cpifinancial.net/bme/news/lebanon-forms-new-government-after-three-months-of-protest|title=Lebanon forms new government after three months of protest|access-date=22 January 2020|website=CPI Financial|date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n{{See also|Cedar Revolution|2006\u201308 Lebanese protests|2015\u201316 Lebanese protests}}\n=== Political background ===\nAccording to ''[[The Economist]]'', Lebanon's dysfunction and mismanagement, a cause of the protests, has its origins in the country's sectarian political system enshrined following the [[Taif agreement]], which took place in 1989, almost thirty years before the 2019 protest began. The Taif agreement enshrines a sect-based political system, where political authority is allocated based on the religious affiliation of the public servant. This system is perceived as exploited by the current Lebanese politicians, many of whom are [[Lebanese Civil War]]-era sectarian warlords who still occupy positions of power and enjoy amnesty against accountability.<ref name=\"veconomist\" >{{cite news|author=|title=A surge of public anger sends Lebanon's politicians reeling|url=https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2019/10/26/a-surge-of-public-anger-sends-lebanons-politicians-reeling|work=[[The Economist]]|date=26 October 2019}}</ref> Lebanon is a mosaic of various religious factions. It is composed of 18 different sects. The 18 officially recognized religious groups include four Muslim sects, 12 Christian sects, the Druze sect, and Judaism.<ref name=\"vglobalsecurity\" >{{cite news|author=|title=Lebanon - Religious Sects|url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/lebanon/religious-sects.htm|work=[[Global Security]]|}}</ref>\n\nThe outbreak of the protests was attributed to the accumulated crises within the preceding weeks in Lebanon. First of all, in Chouf and Saadiyat, among other places, fires have propagated, scorching nearby homes, and placing many people in danger. A large portion of greenery, an aspect of Lebanon that Lebanese people take pride in, was burnt down as a result. The Lebanese government failed to employ its planes to extinguish the fires and had to rely on Cypriotic aid.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2019/10/05/a-long-feared-currency-crisis-has-begun-to-bite-in-lebanon|title=A long-feared currency crisis has begun to bite in Lebanon|date=5 October 2019|work=The Economist|access-date=18 October 2019|issn=0013-0613}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190926-lebanon-gas-stations-to-go-on-strike-over-dollar-shortage|title=Lebanon gas stations to go on strike over dollar 'shortage'|date=26 September 2019|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191018-protests-spread-across-lebanon-over-proposed-new-taxes-1|title=Protests spread across Lebanon over proposed new taxes|date=18 October 2019|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/Business/Local/2019/Sep-25/492238-lebanese-millers-say-wheat-reserves-fall-due-to-ongoing-dollar-problem.ashx|title=Lebanese millers say wheat reserves fall due to ongoing 'dollar problem'|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=18 October 2019|date=25 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://7news.com.au/politics/lebanon-protests-over-whatsapp-tax-plan-c-510336|title=Protests sweep Lebanon for a second day|date=18 October 2019|website=7NEWS.com.au|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> Moreover, the prices of both oil and bread had been increasing amid increased unemployment and poverty nationwide, with youth unemployment at 37% and general unemployment at 25% as of August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.annahar.com/article/1004952-unemployment-the-paralysis-of-lebanese-youth|title=Unemployment: The paralysis of Lebanese youth|date=2 August 2019|website=[[An-Nahar]]|language=en|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref> Since all of these issues are due to a lack of proper governance, the Lebanese people voiced out their opinions over the negative situation.\n\nFurthermore, Lebanon has not had stable, 24-hour electricity since 1975, with eight-hour daily power rationing cuts being common across the nation; obtaining 24-hour electricity in Lebanon has since been dependent on obtaining a deal with the country's \"generator mafia\", which operates a ring of contraband gasoline power generators that contribute to the high level of air pollution observed in Lebanese cities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/ajimpact/energy-problems-fuel-protests-lebanon-eyes-gas-revolution-191025220314003.html|title=As energy problems fuel protests, Lebanon eyes gas revolution|website=Al Jazeera|language=en-US|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> Lebanon has also not had access to drinking water except through purchasing bottled water through private companies since the 1975-1990 [[Lebanese Civil War]]. Finally, the country suffers from a deficient sanitation and sewage infrastructure, which led to the 2015 \"garbage crisis\" that sparked the [[2015\u201316 Lebanese protests]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/lebanon-what-protests-against-the-sectarian-elite-mean-for-hezbollah-126224|title=Lebanon: what protests against the sectarian elite mean for Hezbollah|website=The Conversation|language=en-US|access-date=11 November 2019|date=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nDays before the protests began, a series of about 100 major [[2019 Lebanon forest fires|wildfires]] in Chouf, Khroub and other Lebanese areas displaced hundreds of people and caused enormous damage to Lebanese wildlife. The Lebanese government failed to deploy its firefighting equipment due to lack of maintenance and had to rely on aid from neighboring [[Cyprus]], [[Jordan]], [[Turkey]] and [[Greece]].<ref>{{cite news|author=|title=Lebanon wildfires: Hellish scenes in mountains south of Beirut|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/hellish-scenes-wildfires-engulf-lebanon-191015191252866.html|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=16 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.annahar.com/article/1049862-lebanons-wildfires-call-for-an-appropriate-disaster-risk-management-plan|title=Lebanon's wildfires call for an appropriate disaster risk management plan|last=Khamis|first=Reem|date=16 October 2019|website=An-Nahar|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nProtests started taking place in small numbers around Beirut towards the end of September.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/09/lebanon-protests-worsening-economic-crisis-190929181517574.html|title=Lebanon: Protests over worsening economic crisis|website=aljazeera.com|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/watch-protests-in-lebanons-capital-over-worsening-economic-crisis-1.66769380|title=Watch: Protests in Lebanon's capital over worsening economic crisis|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> Impetus for the revolutionary movement was apparent years before the protests began and was visible in Lebanon's arts and culture scene, as evidenced by pop artist [[Ragheb Alama]]'s song \"Tar Al Balad\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/lebanese-mp-hikmat-dib-calls-for-the-beheading-of-lebanese-pop-star-ragheb-alameh-1.1544619494498|title=Lebanese MP Hikmat Dib calls for the beheading of Lebanese pop star Ragheb Alameh|website=gulfnews.com|language=en|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref> in December 2018 and rock singer-songwriter [[IJK (singer songwriter)|IJK]]'s song \"Chedd Halak\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Imad Jack Karam (IJK) on La Bonne HUmeur|url=https://soundcloud.com/lightfmlebanon/imad-jack-karam-ijk-on-la-bonne-humeur|language=en|access-date=10 November 2019}}</ref> in June 2019.\n\n=== Economic background ===\nSince 1997, successive governments maintained a [[Fixed exchange rate system|pegged exchange rate]] between the [[Lebanese pound]] and [[United States dollar]].<ref>Brennan, Sam (24 September 2019). [https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/09/lebanon-fixed-currency-exchange-rate-economic-stability.html A closer look into Lebanon\u2019s fixed currency]. ''Al Monitor''. Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref> Forecasts for the [[Economy of Lebanon|Lebanese economy]] worsened over the 2010s and by 2019 [[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita|GDP per capita]] reached its lowest since 2008 and the [[debt-to-GDP ratio]] reached its highest since 2008 at 151%.<ref>[https://data.worldbank.org/country/lebanon Lebanon]. World Bank. Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.arabtimesonline.com/news/the-tragic-disintegration-of-lebanon/ The tragic disintegration of Lebanon]. ''Arab Times'' (11 October 2019). Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref> As a result, international [[credit rating agencies]] downgraded the rating of government bonds.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/lebanon-economy-moodys/update-1-moodys-puts-lebanons-caa1-rating-under-review-for-downgrade-idUSL5N26M54E  UPDATE 1-Moody's puts Lebanon's Caa1 rating under review for downgrade]. Reuters (1 October 2019). Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref> The combination of an economic downturn in the import-dependent country with the continuation of its dollar peg saw an increase in the government's budget deficit and a reliance on using [[foreign exchange reserves]] from the [[Banque du Liban|nation's central bank]] to keep the currency peg.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2019/10/05/a-long-feared-currency-crisis-has-begun-to-bite-in-lebanon A long-feared currency crisis has begun to bite in Lebanon]. ''The Economist'' (5 October 2019). Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref> A subsequent dollar shortage in late 2019 further affected the economy, as import businesses and citizens became unable to acquire dollars at the official rate and a black market emerged.<ref>Holtmeier, Lauren (7 October 2019). [https://english.alarabiya.net/en/business/economy/2019/10/07/How-the-Lebanese-pound-peg-began-to-crack-under-pressure-.html  How Lebanon\u2019s dollar shortage sparked an economic crisis]. ''Al Arabiya''. Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.france24.com/en/20190926-lebanon-gas-stations-to-go-on-strike-over-dollar-shortage  Lebanon gas stations to go on strike over dollar 'shortage']. France 24 (26 September 2019). Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref> The [[Lebanese government of January 2019|coalition government]] led by [[Saad Hariri]] responded with an [[austerity]] program of general tax increases and spending reductions, with the aim to reduce the government deficit while maintaining the peg against the U.S. dollar.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/lebanon-protests-hariri/lebanon-approves-2020-budget-with-06-deficit-hariri-idUSL5N2765G8 Lebanon approves 2020 budget with 0.6% deficit - Hariri]. Reuters. Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-economy/lebanon-banks-suck-in-dollars-to-maintain-peg-but-economy-stagnates-idUSKBN1L11IR Lebanon banks suck in dollars to maintain peg, but economy stagnates]. Reuters (16 August 2018). Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/ajimpact/lebanon-parliament-passes-2019-austerity-budget-190719202325329.html Lebanon's parliament passes 2019 austerity budget]. ''Al Jazeera'' (19 July 2019). Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref> The reduction of the national deficit was a condition of a package of [[USD]] 10.2 billion of loans and [[USD]] 860 million of grants agreed in 2018 with the [[World Bank]], [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]], and [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref>Irish, John & Pennetier, Marine (6 April 2018). [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-economy-france/lebanon-wins-pledges-exceeding-11-billion-in-paris-idUSKCN1HD0UU Lebanon wins pledges exceeding $11 billion in Paris]. Reuters. Retrieved 21 October 2019.</ref>\n\nOn 1 October, the Central Bank of Lebanon announced an economic strategy that promised to provide dollars to all those companies in the business of importing wheat, gasoline, and pharmaceuticals, so that they could continue their imports. This was considered a short-term solution by economic analysts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/10/lebanon-protests-economic-conditions-central-bank-government.html|title=Protesters rise up as Lebanon's leaders grapple with multiple economic crises|last=Kranz|first=Michal|date=4 October 2019|website=Al-Monitor|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a cabinet session held on 17 October, the government proposed strategies to increase state revenue for 2020. There were 36 items to be discussed, including the increase of Value Added Tax (VAT) by 2pp by 2021 and an additional 2pp by 2022, making it reach a total of 15%. Additionally, the media reported there were plans of a [[USD]] 0.20 charge on [[Voice over IP|Voice over Internet Protocol]] (VoIP) calls, such as ones made on [[FaceTime]], [[Facebook]] and [[WhatsApp]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-17/493731-cabinet-meets-as-backlash-grows-over-tax-proposals.ashx|title=Cabinet meets as backlash grows over tax proposals|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> The final session of the budget draft was to be held on 19 October, but was canceled upon the agreement of [[Prime Minister of Lebanon|Prime Minister]] [[Saad Hariri]] and [[President of Lebanon|President]] [[Michel Aoun]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-economy-idUSKBN1WW20B|title=Lebanon cabinet sets 'final session' on Friday for 2020 draft budget: minister|date=17 October 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=18 October 2019|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.english.almanar.com.lb/850654|title=Hariri Contacts Aoun, Both Men Agree to Cancel Today's Cabinet Session \u2013 Al-Manar TV Lebanon|website=english.almanar.com.lb|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== 2019 Protests ==\n\n=== Beginning ===\n[[File:Mohammad Al-Amin Mosque during 2019 Lebanese revolution.jpg|alt=|thumb|Protests in [[Antelias|Lebanon]]]]\nOn 17 October 2019, approximately one hundred civil activists were protesting against the new proposed taxes in and around downtown [[Beirut]], blocking important streets.<ref name=\"Lebanon_17Oct2019_start\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/lebanese-protesters-set-barricades-block-main-roads-191028090151931.html|title=Lebanese protesters set up barricades, block main roads|date=28 October 2019|access-date=13 November 2019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219202434/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/lebanese-protesters-set-barricades-block-main-roads-191028090151931.html |archivedate=19 December 2019}}</ref> As the [[Ministry of Education and Higher Education (Lebanon)|Minister of Higher Education]] [[Akram Chehayeb]] and his convoy passed by the area, protesters assembled on his car. One of his bodyguards shot stray bullets into the air, which further enraged the protesters; no injuries were reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.annahar.com/article/1051479-whatsapp-tax-the-final-straw-as-protests-erupts|title=WhatsApp tax the final straw as massive protests erupt|first=Georgi|last=Azar|date=17 October 2019|website=An-Nahar|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> [[Walid Joumblatt]], the leader of the [[Progressive Socialist Party]], stated that he had spoken to minister Chehayeb who represents the party in the Lebanese government and requested the bodyguards be handed over to the police, as all people are \"under the law\".<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1184900158817034240|user=walidjoumblatt|title=\u0627\u0646\u0646\u064a \u0637\u0644\u0628\u062a \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0641\u064a\u0642 \u0627\u0643\u0631\u0645 \u0634\u0647\u064a\u0628 \u062a\u0633\u0644\u064a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0630\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0637\u0644\u0642\u0648\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0647\u0648\u0627\u0621 \u0648\u0646\u062d\u0646 \u062a\u062d\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u0644\u0643\u0646 \u0646\u0637\u0644\u0628 \u062a\u062d\u0642\u064a\u0642 \u0634\u0641\u0627\u0641 \u0648\u0646\u0631\u0641\u0636 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0639\u062a\u062f\u0627\u0621 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u064a\u0627 \u0643\u0627\u0646 .pic.twitter.com/LUo2mCghCI|date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/17/middleeast/lebanon-protests-economy-intl/index.html|title=WhatsApp tax sparks night of austerity protests across Lebanon|author=Tamara Qiblawi|website=CNN|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> A large number of protesters began appearing in [[Martyrs' Square, Beirut|Martyrs Square]], [[Beirut Central District|Nejmeh Square]], and [[Hamra Street]], as well as many other regions around Lebanon. As the protests grew bigger, [[Prime Minister of Lebanon|Prime Minister]] [[Saad Hariri]] called a snap cabinet meeting at the request of [[President of Lebanon|President]] [[Michel Aoun]] for midday on 18 October.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/news/live_feed/976877/president_aoun_called_pm_hariri_and_agreed_to_hold_a_cabinet_meeting_tomorrow_at_baabda_palace|title=President Aoun called PM Hariri and agreed to hold a Cabinet meeting tomorrow at Baabda Palace|website=MTV Lebanon|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> An announcement was also made by Minister of Higher Education [[Akram Chehayeb]] that all schools and universities, public or private, would remain closed the next day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/news/live_feed/976960/education_minister_akram_chehayeb_issues_statement_to_close_public_and_private_schools_and_universities_tomorrow_(friday)_because_of_the_current_situation_in_the_country|title=Education Minister Akram Chehayeb issues statement to close public and private schools and universities tomorrow (Friday) because of the current situation in the country|website=MTV Lebanon|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> The Minister of Telecommunications Mohamad Choucair announced that the \"WhatsApp tax\" idea had been scrapped at around 11:00PM.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lebanon scraps WhatsApp fee amid violent protests |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-economy-calls/lebanon-scraps-whatsapp-fee-amid-violent-protests-idUKKBN1WW1ZA |access-date=21 October 2019 |work=Reuters |date=18 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Protesters saw the \"WhatsApp tax\" as the last straw, socially, politically and economically, against the entire political class, which was deemed corrupt and in need of immediate ousting.\n\n[[File:RiadElSolh 22Oct2019.jpg|thumb|Protesters in Riad el Solh square, [[Beirut]]. 22 October 2019.]]\nProtesters in [[Nabatieh|Nabatiyeh]] and [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]], on 18 October, vandalized the offices of the [[Hezbollah]], [[Amal Movement]], and [[Free Patriotic Movement]] political parties in an expression of disillusionment and in protest against perceived government corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/1191546/des-manifestants-sen-prennent-aux-domiciles-et-bureaux-de-responsables-amal-et-hezbollah-a-nabatiye.html|title=Des manifestants s'en prennent aux domiciles et bureaux de responsables Amal et Hezbollah \u00e0 Nabatiy\u00e9|date=18 October 2019|website=L'Orient-Le Jour|language=fr|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-18/493786-some-protesters-riot-in-central-beirut-hurl-stones-at-riot-police-shatter-shops-windows.ashx|title=Some protesters riot in central Beirut, hurl stones at riot police, shatter shops' windows|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/1191553/liban-tentative-de-penetrer-dans-les-bureaux-du-cpl-a-tripoli-la-route-au-akkar-coupee.html|title=Liban : le bureau du CPL \u00e0 Tripoli saccag\u00e9|date=18 October 2019|website=L'Orient-Le Jour|language=fr|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> Other protesters aimed to enter the Serail, which includes the Lebanese [[Parliament of Lebanon|Parliament]] building, but were stopped by the use of tear gas from the Internal Security Forces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-18/493787-police-fire-tear-gas-at-rioting-protesters-near-govt-seat-in-central-beirut.ashx|title=Police fire tear gas at rioting protesters near govt seat in central Beirut|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> protesters created roadblocks on the major roads of the country, using burning tires and trash cans to stop access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/1191569/protestations-de-nombreuses-routes-coupees-a-travers-le-liban.html|title=Protestations : de nombreuses routes coup\u00e9es \u00e0 travers le Liban|date=18 October 2019|website=L'Orient-Le Jour|language=fr|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-18/493791-roads-across-lebanon-blocked-following-overnight-protests.ashx|title=Lebanon paralyzed after second day of protests|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> Civil servants announced a strike with immediate effect through League of Public Sector Employees, arguing that the proposed reforms would \"undermine the rights of employees and pensioners in particular\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/1191550/liban-greve-generale-vendredi-de-toutes-les-administrations-publiques.html|title=Liban : \"gr\u00e8ve g\u00e9n\u00e9rale\" vendredi de \"toutes les administrations publiques\"|date=18 October 2019|website=L'Orient-Le Jour|language=fr|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> A cabinet meeting was due to be held in the afternoon, but ministers of the [[Lebanese Forces]] announced that they would not attend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-18/493798-lebanese-forces-will-not-participate-in-todays-cabinet-session-minister.ashx|title=Lebanese Forces will not participate in today's Cabinet session: minister|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> The leader of the Forces, [[Samir Geagea]], called for the resignation of the Prime Minister, due to the \"resounding failure to halt the deterioration of the [country's] economic situation\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/1191589/geagea-appelle-hariri-a-demissionner.html|title=Geagea appelle Hariri \u00e0 d\u00e9missionner|date=18 October 2019|website=L'Orient-Le Jour|language=fr|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> After this announcement, the cabinet meeting was canceled by the Prime Minister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-18/493801-lf-ministers-will-not-participate-in-cabinet-session-chidiac.ashx|title=Hariri to address the nation at 6 p.m.|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> Leader of the [[Progressive Socialist Party]], [[Walid Jumblatt]], called for a \"calm and peaceful\" move against President [[Michel Aoun]]'s mandate, and organized rallies in [[Aley]], [[Bhamdoun]], and [[Baakline]] to voice their opinions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/1191608/joumblatt-appelle-a-un-mouvement-pacifique-contre-le-mandat-aoun.html|title=Joumblatt appelle \u00e0 un \"mouvement pacifique contre le mandat\" Aoun|date=18 October 2019|website=L'Orient-Le Jour|language=fr|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> [[Pierre Issa]] of the [[National Bloc (Lebanon)|National Bloc]] voiced a similar opinion, calling for a \"government of specialists, a government reduced from public safety\". However, he criticized the involvement of political parties within the protests and argued it should remain something for the citizens to do.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/1191610/pierre-issa-si-le-cabinet-demissionne-il-faudra-former-un-gouvernement-reduit-de-salut-public.html|title=Pierre Issa \u00e0 L'OLJ : Si le cabinet d\u00e9missionne, il faudra former un gouvernement r\u00e9duit de salut public - Zeina ANTONIOS|last=ANTONIOS|first=Zeina|date=18 October 2019|website=L'Orient-Le Jour|language=fr|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> In the evening, Prime Minister Saad Hariri addressed the nation, giving his \"partners in government\" 72 hours to support the reforms. If they did not come to an agreement, he suggested he would take a \"different approach\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/news/live_feed/977617/hariri_we_can_no_longer_wait_for_our_partners_in_the_government_to_start_working_on_the_solution,_so_either_they_show_in_the_coming_72_hours_that_they_are_serious_about_reforms_or_i_will_take_a_different_approach|title=Hariri: We can no longer wait for our 'partners in the government' to start working on the solution, so either they show in the coming 72 hours that they are serious about reforms or I will take a different approach|website=MTV Lebanon|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/news/live_feed/977618/hariri_partners_in_the_government_have_72_hours_to_give_me_their_answer|title=Hariri: 'Partners in the government' have 72 hours to give me their answer|website=MTV Lebanon|language=en|access-date=18 October 2019}}</ref> He tweeted \"72 hours...\" right after the delivered speech.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1185224921254973441|user=saadhariri|title=#\u0667\u0662\u0633\u0627\u0639\u0629 ...|date=18 October 2019|}}</ref>\n\n=== First week: 19\u201324 October ===\n{{multiple image\n | align = left\n | total_width = 320\n | image1 = Mohammad_Al-Amin_Mosque_during_2019_Lebanese_revolution.jpg\n | caption1 = Protesters wave Lebanon's flag in [[Beirut]]. [[Mohammad Al-Amin Mosque]], 20 October 2019\n\n | image2 = Sign_held_during_Lebanese_Protest_displays_disapproval_of_Lebanon's_Government_\"Parliament_of_Thieves\".jpg\n | caption2 = Sign held during Lebanese Protest displays disapproval of Lebanese Government &#x22;Parliament of thieves&#x22;. [[Beirut]], 20 October 2019\n}}\n\nLebanese national Hussein Al-Attar was shot and killed during a protest on 19 October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the961.com/people/the-first-lebanese-to-tragically-lose-his-life-protesting-for-a-better-lebanon/|title=The First Lebanese to Tragically Lose His Life Protesting for a Better Lebanon/|last=The961|first=News|date=21 October 2019|website=the961.com|language=en-EN|access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref> Former MP Mosbah al-Ahdab's bodyguards fired on protesters, no one was killed, but four were injured.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://libnanews.com/liban-flash-7-blesses-a-tripoli-suite-a-une-fusillade/|title=Liban/Flash: 2 morts et 4 bless\u00e9s \u00e0 Tripoli suite \u00e0 une fusillade|last=Libnanews|first=Newsdesk|date=18 October 2019|website=Libnanews, Le M\u00e9dia Citoyen du Liban|language=fr-FR|access-date=19 October 2019}}</ref> The General Secretary of [[Hezbollah]], [[Hassan Nasrallah]], addressed the nation in the morning, speaking against the imposed taxes. However, he indicated that Hezbollah was against the government resigning and instead asked citizens to divert blame from Hariri's cabinet to the previous government, which was also to blame for the state of the economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/news/live_feed/978002/nasrallah_there_are_political_leaders_and_forces_in_lebanon_that_act_above_everyone_else_and_avoid_all_responsibilities_for_the_past_and_the_present_mistakes_and_blame_others|title=Nasrallah: There are political leaders and forces in Lebanon that act above everyone else and avoid all responsibilities for the past and the present mistakes and blame others|website=MTV Lebanon|language=en|access-date=19 October 2019}}</ref> As the protests carried on throughout the day, there were alleged reports of [[Amal Movement]] militant groups harassing and opening fire on protesters in [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=yumnafawaz|number=1185498183184588800|title=\"\u063a\u0646\u0645\u060c \u062e\u0648\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0641 \u062a\u0627\u0628\u0639\u064a\u0646 \u0648\u0631\u0627 \u0627\u062d\u0632\u0627\u0628\u0643\u0646\"\u0635\u0631\u062e\u0629 \u0645\u0646 \u0645\u062a\u0638\u0627\u0647\u0631\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0635\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0649 \u0646\u0628\u064a\u0647 \u0628\u0631\u064a \u0628\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0639\u062a\u062f\u0627\u0621\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0646\u0643\u064a\u0644 \u0645\u0646 \u0642\u0628\u0644 \u0634\u0628\u0627\u0628 \u062d\u0631\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0645\u0644.#\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646_\u064a\u0646\u062a\u0641\u0636 #\u0627\u0644\u0632\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0646_\u0641\u0644\u062a\u0627\u0646\u0629pic.twitter.com/FPZoc8DbOS ||date=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nProtests were held around major European cities, as well as in North America and Australia, showing solidarity with the protesters in Lebanon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-19/493886-hundreds-across-the-world-protest-in-solidarity-with-lebanon.ashx|title=Hundreds across the world protest in solidarity with Lebanon|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=19 October 2019}}</ref> Due to the mounting pressure from protesters, the [[Lebanese Forces]] announced their resignation from the cabinet. Samir Geagea, their leader, had previously blamed his opponents for \"obstructing the necessary reforms,\" but since declared his \"lack of confidence in the current cabinet.\" His party held four seats within the government: Minister of Labor [[Camille Abou Sleiman]], Minister of Administrative Development [[May Chidiac]], Deputy Prime Minister [[Ghassan Hasbani]], and Minister of Social Affairs [[Richard Kouyumdjian|Richard Kouyumjian]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.annahar.com/article/1052943-lebanese-forces-resign-from-cabinet|title=Lebanese Forces resign from Cabinet |first=Georgi|last=Azar|date=20 October 2019|website=An-Nahar|access-date=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 October, hundreds of thousands of protesters gathered in locations throughout the country, making it the largest demonstrations since 2005.<ref name=BBC21Oct>{{cite news |title=Lebanon's leaders move to quell huge protests |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-50118300 |access-date=21 October 2019 |work=BBC News |date=21 October 2019}}</ref> Gunfire was heard outside the Tripoli office of Firas Al-Ali, an associate of Hariri. None were injured with the clash, and security forces were quick to act.<ref>{{cite news |title=Clash and gunfire in Tripoli, but no casualties |url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/News/Local/978942/Clash_and_gunfire_in_Tripoli,_but_no_casualties |access-date=26 October 2019 |work=MTV Lebanon |date=20 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> At 6:00PM, protesters across the country united to sing the [[Lebanese National Anthem|national anthem]] together.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lebanese national anthem unites demonstrations at 6:00PM |url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/News/Local/978814/Lebanese_national_anthem_unites_demonstrations_at_6_pm |access-date=26 October 2019 |work=MTV Lebanon |date=20 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n[[File:Thawra Protests TyreSourLebanon RomanDeckert22102019.webm|left|thumb|310x310px|Video of protesters in Tyre cheering a female activist singer on 22 October 2019]]\nOn 21 October, a general strike was called across the country demanding an end to the country's economic problems. Some protesters began clearing away demonstration debris in Beirut after a social media call to keep the streets tidy and clear.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lebanon protests: All the latest updates |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/lebanon-protests-latest-updates-191021080734203.html |access-date=21 October 2019 |work=aljazeera.com |date=21 October 2019}}</ref> In the afternoon, an emergency cabinet meeting was held. After the meeting, Prime Minister Hariri held a press conference in which he announced various economic reforms including halfing the salaries of legislators and members of parliament, reducing the deficit by about US$3.4 billion in 2020 with the help of the Lebanese central bank and the banking sector, distributing financial aid to families living in poverty and giving US$160 million in housing loans.<ref name=BBC21Oct/> These proposals were unsuccessful at quelling protests. At night, several motorcyclists hoisting Hezbollah and Amal Movement were recorded heading towards the protests in central Beirut but were intercepted by the Lebanese Army. Soon thereafter, Hezbollah and the Amal Movement denied any involvement with the motorcyclists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-21/494023-army-foiled-attempted-infiltration-of-beirut-protest-source.ashx|title=Army foiled attempted infiltration of Beirut protest: source|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:GrandSerial 23Oct2019.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Protesters in front of the Grand Serial, [[Beirut]], carrying a sign that reads \"No to Sectarian Rule\". 23 October 2019.]]\n\nHariri met on 22 October with [[ambassador]]s from the [[United States]], [[Russia]], [[France]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Germany]], [[Italy]], and the [[European Union]], along with representatives from [[China]], the [[United Nations]], and the [[Arab League]]. Hariri discussed planned reforms and stressed the importance of peaceful expression from the protesters. The representatives, who form the International Support Group for Lebanon, expressed support for economic reforms and protection of protesters, but urged the leaders of Lebanon to engage in open dialogue with the country's citizens.<ref>{{cite news |title=ISG visits Hariri: Support for the reform objectives endorsed by the Cabinet |url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/News/Local/979989/ISG_visits_Hariri_Support_for_the_reform_objectives_endorsed_by_the_Cabinet |access-date=26 October 2019 |work=MTV Lebanon |date=22 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 October, Hariri held a meeting with the ministerial committee in charge of financial and economic reforms, discussing a draft law on the recovery of public money and requesting suggestions on it from the Supreme Judicial Council within ten days.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hariri chairs meeting on looted public money recovery law |url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/News/Local/980557/Hariri_chairs_meeting_on_looted_public_money_recovery_law |access-date=26 October 2019 |work=MTV Lebanon |date=23 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In the evening, Hariri also held a meeting with members of the [[Progressive Socialist Party]] to discuss the latest developments in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hariri receives PSP delegation |url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/News/Local/980579/Hariri_receives_PSP_delegation |access-date=26 October 2019 |work=MTV Lebanon |date=23 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Sheikh Akl of the Lebanese [[Lebanese Druze|Druze community]] called for government dialogue to safeguard the rights of liberty, security and stability.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sheikh Akl calls for preserving people's rights |url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/News/Local/980576/Sheikh_Akl_calls_for_preserving_peoples_rights |access-date=26 October 2019 |work=MTV Lebanon |date=23 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nPresident Michel Aoun addressed the population on 24 October, stating his willingness to hold a dialogue with the protesters and find the best solution forward. He supported Hariri's reforms, but did confirm a need to \"review the current government\" within the \"state institutions\", and not through protesting.<ref>{{cite news |title='I am waiting for you': Lebanon's Aoun invites protesters to talk |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/waiting-lebanon-aoun-invites-protesters-talk-191024112324367.html |access-date=25 October 2019 |work=aljazeera.com |date=24 October 2019}}</ref> Hariri supported this review through Lebanon's \"constitutional mechanisms\", but the protesters rejected any calls for dialogue until the government has resigned.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lebanese protesters reject president's appeal for talks |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/lebanese-protesters-reject-president-appeal-talks-191024193706720.html |work=aljazeera.com |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Second week: 25\u201331 October ===\nDespite calls for dialogue from President Aoun, protests and road blocks continued on 25 October 2019. Small scuffles broke out in central Beirut between protesters and Hezbollah supporters. One protester was injured.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lebanon protesters reject concessions, block key roads |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191025-lebanon-protesters-reject-concessions-block-key-roads |access-date=25 October 2019 |work=France 24 |date=25 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> A report by [[Standard & Poor's]] downgraded its credit assessment of Lebanon to \"CreditWatch negative\" due to the government's low creditworthiness and economic pressures relating to the reforms. The country's banks remained closed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hezbollah to speak on Lebanon crisis as economic warning issued |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/hezbollah-speak-lebanon-crisis-economic-warning-issued-191025091338462.html |access-date=25 October 2019 |work=aljazeera.com |date=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Roads closed as pressure builds on govt in 9th day of uprising|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-25/494299-roads-closed-as-pressure-builds-on-govt-in-9th-day-of-uprising.ashx |website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=25 October 2019|date=25 October 2019}}</ref> Hezbollah supporters again clashed with protesters in downtown Beirut, chanting in support of Hezbollah's General Secretary, Hassan Nasrallah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-25/494317-riot-police-scuffle-with-hezbollah-supporters.ashx|title=Hezbollah supporters clash with riot police, protesters|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=25 October 2019}}</ref> Nasrallah held a speech in the evening, calling his supporters to leave the streets.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nasrallah to talk domestic developments|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-25/494307-nasrallah-to-talk-domestic-developments.ashx|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=25 October 2019|date=25 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-25/494319-hezbollah-calls-on-supporters-to-withdraw-from-protests-listen-to-nasrallahs-speech.ashx|title=Hezbollah calls on supporters to withdraw from protests, listen to Nasrallah's speech|website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=25 October 2019}}</ref> Within this speech, he praised the protesters for achieving economic reforms, but suggested that they were being exploited by local and foreign agents to start a civil war within the country.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cheeseman |first1=Abbie |title=Hizbollah leader warns of civil war after days of Lebanon protests |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/25/hezbollah-leader-warns-civil-war-weeks-lebanon-protests/ |access-date=25 October 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=25 October 2019}}</ref> Nasrallah also strongly suggested that the protests are part of an Israeli and American plot.<ref name=\"veconomist2\" >{{cite news|author=|title= Saad Hariri, the prime minister of Lebanon, steps down|url= https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2019/10/29/saad-hariri-the-prime-minister-of-lebanon-steps-down|work=[[The Economist]]|date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nA security meeting was held on 26 October in [[Yarzeh]] to discuss how the safety and free movement of protesters could be ensured.<ref>{{cite news |title=Meeting at Army Command to discuss current situation |url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/News/Local/981850/Meeting_at_Army_Command_to_discuss_current_situation |access-date=26 October 2019 |work=MTV Lebanon |date=26 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> [[Lebanese Forces]] leader Samir Geagea once more criticized the lack of response from the government towards the protesters' concerns.<ref>{{cite news |title=Geagea criticizes neglect of people's demands |url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/en/News/Local/981854/Geagea_criticizes_neglect_of_peoples_demands |access-date=26 October 2019 |work=MTV Lebanon |date=26 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Meanwhile, thousands of Lebanese gathered in over thirty cities around the world on the 26 and 27 October including [[Sydney]], [[Paris]], [[Houston]] and [[London]] in a show of support{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}.\n\n[[File:Human chain martyr place beirut oct 27 2019.jpg|thumb|220x220px|Human Chain on Martyr place in [[Beirut]] (27 October)]]\nTens of thousands of individuals took part in a \"human chain\" which was held on 27 October at the coastlines from the Northern city of Tripoli to the southern city of Tyre - encompassing 171&nbsp;km - organized with the intention to show the unity of the Lebanese people.<ref>{{cite news |title= Protesters Just Formed a Human Chain Across Lebanon|url=https://www.the961.com/news/united-human-chain-forms-across-lebanon-on-11th-day-of-protest |access-date=27 October 2019 |work=The961 |date=27 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/news/\u0645\u0640\u0640\u062d\u0640\u0640\u0644\u0640\u0640\u064a\u0640\u0640\u0627\u062a/982210/\u0633\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0629_\u0645\u0646_\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062d\u062a\u062c\u064a\u0646_\u0627\u0645\u062a\u062f\u062a_\u0645\u0646_\u0635\u0648\u0631_\u0628\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647_\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635|title=\u0633\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0629 \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062d\u062a\u062c\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0645\u062a\u062f\u062a \u0645\u0646 \u0635\u0648\u0631 \u0628\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0635|website=MTV Lebanon|language=ar|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/lebanon-protesters-form-human-chain-country-191027113442407.html|title=Lebanon protesters form human chain across the country|website=aljazeera.com|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref> The Maronite Patriarch [[Bechara Boutros al-Rahi]] during a Sunday [[sermon]] in [[Bkerk\u00e9]] considered that the people are living their positive and reformist revolution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mtv.com.lb/news/\u0645\u0640\u0640\u062d\u0640\u0640\u0644\u0640\u0640\u064a\u0640\u0640\u0627\u062a/982093/\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0639\u064a_\u0644\u0627_\u062a\u0646\u0638\u0631\u0648\u0627_\u0627\u0644\u0649_\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064f\u062a\u0638\u0627\u0647\u0631\u064a\u0646_\u0628\u0641\u0648\u0642\u064a\u0651\u0629_\u0648\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0631|title=\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0639\u064a: \u0644\u0627 \u062a\u0646\u0638\u0631\u0648\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u064f\u062a\u0638\u0627\u0647\u0631\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u0641\u0648\u0642\u064a\u0651\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0643\u0628\u0627\u0631|website=MTV Lebanon|language=ar|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref> [[Pope Francis]] addressed the Lebanese people expressing their struggle in the face of challenges and social, moral and economic problems of the country, expressing he's praying that Lebanon can continue to be a place of peaceful coexistence, and urging the Lebanese government to listen to the concerns of the people.<ref>{{cite news |title= Pope Francis Addressed the Lebanese Revolutionaries in a Message of Support|url=https://www.the961.com/news/pope-francis-addressed-the-lebanese-revolutionaries-in-a-message-of-support |access-date=27 October 2019 |work=The961 |date=27 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBlack-clad<ref name=\"veconomist2\" /> Hezbollah and Amal Movement supporters attacked protesters in Beirut on 29 October, tearing down and setting fire to the tents set up by the protesters, throwing plastic chairs, and beating anti-government protesters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/amal-and-hezbollah-supporters-overrun-beirut-protesters-1.930249|title=Amal and Hezbollah supporters overrun Beirut protesters|website=The National|language=en|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref> Many among the angry mob chanted: \"God, Nasrallah, and the whole Dahyeh,\" in reference to the southern suburb that is a stronghold of the Iranian-backed militant group. They also chanted, \"Shia, Shia\", as a reverential reference to the country's [[Shiite]] Muslim sect.<ref name=\"veconomist2\" /> The Hezbollah and Amal Movement supporters also attacked TV crew members and destroyed live broadcasting equipment for the [[MTV (Lebanon)]] and [[Al Jadeed]] television channels, claiming that they were upset at the roadblocks and insults to their leader.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/hezbollah-supporters-break-lebanon-protest-camp|title=Hezbollah Supporters Break Up Lebanon Protest Camp|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref> Public squares across Beirut filled with protesters shortly after.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/lebanese-prime-minister-saad-hariri-announces-he-will-resign-after-nearly-two-weeks-of-protests/2019/10/29/bd9e7cf2-fa49-11e9-8906-ab6b60de9124_story.html|title=Lebanese Prime Minister Saad Hariri announces he will resign after nearly two weeks of protests|last=Dadouch|first=Sarah|last2=Khattab|first2=Asser|date=29 October 2019|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref> [[Prime Minister]] [[Saad Hariri]] announced his resignation in a televised address on the afternoon of 29 October. Several hours after the resignation of the Prime Minister, celebrations swept the nation with demonstrators cautiously welcoming the resignation celebrated through fireworks, songs, and releasing flagged colored balloons.<ref>{{cite news|author=Vivian Yee|date=29 October 2019|title=Lebanon's Prime Minister, Saad Hariri, Steps Down in Face of Protests|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/29/world/middleeast/saad-hariri-stepping-down-lebanon.html?smid=tw-nytimes&smtyp=cur|work=The New York Times|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October, tear gas was fired at protesters in the northern district of Akkar by the Lebanese Army trying to reopen the roads. Protesters also blocked roads in the southern city of Sidon and Bekaa Valley. In Central Beirut, dozens of protesters blocked the \"Ring Bridge\" while a big crowd returned to Tripoli's al-Nour Square to protest. The Lebanese Army intervened in many regions to prevent escalation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Number of roads across Lebanon blocked again |url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-30/494651-number-of-roads-across-lebanon-blocked-again-teargas-fired-at-protesters-in-some-areas.ashx |website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lebanese Army Intervenes to Reopen Roads |url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-30/494599-uprising-day-14-lebanese-army-opens-roads.ashx |website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref> Later that evening a statement released from the Presidential Office said that [[Lebanese President]] [[Michel Aoun]] will address the nation the next day.<ref>{{cite news |title=President Aoun to address the nation on Thursday |url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-30/494625-aoun-to-address-the-nation-on-thursday.ashx |website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nPresident Aoun delivered a speech on 31 October<ref>{{cite news |title=President Michel Aoun addressed the nation Thursday evening |url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-01/494760-presidents-speech-marks-third-anniversary-in-office.ashx |website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref> in which he spoke about Lebanon's economic and financial crisis. He also spoke about his commitment in fighting corruption, ensuring political stability, eliminating terrorists and the return of Syrian refugees within the country. He also promised the new government will be made up by specialist instead of political loyalists.<ref>{{cite news |title=Everything You Need to Know About President Aoun's Speech |url=https://www.the961.com/news/everything-you-need-to-know-about-president-aouns-speech |access-date=31 October 2019 |publisher=The961}}</ref> Protesters took to the streets and blocked roads across the country almost immediately after President Aoun's address to the nation, demanding early parliamentary elections and the formation of a technocratic government. Demonstrators shut off roads in cities nationwide \u2013 including Sidon, Bekaa, and Khaldeh \u2013 with burning tires or by the sheer volume of protesters. In Tripoli, thousands of protesters started to gather at Al-Nour Square while In Beirut, protesters blocked the George Haddad highway which connects the waterfront road to the \"Ring Bridge\". The Lebanese Army and riot police were deployed across the country in an effort to reopen the roads.<ref>{{cite news |title=Protesters take to streets after the President speech |url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-31/494685-security-forces-open-highway-north-of-beirut-other-roads-remain-blocked.ashx |website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Security forces struggle to keep roads open |url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Oct-31/494673-security-forces-struggle-to-keep-roads-open.ashx |website=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Third week: 1\u20137 November ===\nLebanon's banks reopened on 1 November 2019, after two weeks of closure, the longest bank closure in the nation's history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lebanon's banks reopen after two-week closure amid protests|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191101-lebanon-s-banks-reopen-after-two-weeks-of-protests|access-date=11 November 2019|publisher=[[France 24]]}}</ref> \"Unofficial\" capital controls were imposed by individual banks to prevent a [[bank run]], with personal withdrawals being limited to US$3,000 per week or per month depending on individual banks. Corporate banking activity was similarly heavily restricted, and international bank transfers from Lebanon were halted almost completely, subject to manual per-transfer approval.<ref>{{cite news|title=How Unofficial Capital Controls Stopped a Run on the Banks in Lebanon|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2019/11/07/how-unofficial-capital-controls-stopped-a-run-on-the-banks-in-lebanon/|access-date=11 November 2019|publisher=[[CounterPunch]]}}</ref> [[Hezbollah]]'s Secretary General [[Hassan Nasrallah]] offered a public speech in which he stated that Hezbollah feared a government overthrow, due to the consequent \"vacuum\" Lebanon would experience.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Nasrallah Urges Fast Formation of 'Sovereign Govt.', Says 'Strife, Political Coup' Foiled |url=http://www.naharnet.com/stories/en/266053-nasrallah-urges-fast-formation-of-sovereign-govt-says-strife-political-coup-foiled|date=1 November 2019|access-date=22 November 2019|publisher=[[Naharnet]]}}</ref> Nasrallah's then-latest speech was perceived to be unclear on whether Hezbollah supported or opposed the nation-wide revolutionary movement. Nasrallah again shed doubt on the motivations of the protesters during his speech, implying that they were being manipulated by foreign influences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/04/lebanon-shiite-hezbollah-resistance-establishment-protest/|title=Hezbollah's Old Tricks Won't Work in Lebanon|last=Kranz|first=Michal|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> As Lebanese schools universities remained closed during the protests, public teach-ins and debates, organized by secular political groups and advocacy organizations ([[Beirut Madinati]], [[Libaladi]], [[Lihaqqi]] and others) were offered in Beirut.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1190312466019807233|user=habib_b|title=Teach-ins and public debates happening now across the protest space in downtown|date=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tripoli2019LebanonProtests 2Nov2019.jpg|thumb|Protest in [[Tripoli, Lebanon]], a city that was recognized as being a central source of energy for the protest movement.<ref>{{cite news|title=In Lebanon's sweeping protests, hard-hit Tripoli sets the tempo|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-protests-tripoli/in-lebanons-sweeping-protests-hard-hit-tripoli-sets-the-tempo-idUSKBN1XE13J|access-date=11 November 2019 |publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> 2 November 2019.]]\n\nOn 3 November, thousands of Lebanese [[Free Patriotic Movement]] supporters attended a protest in support of President Michel Aoun, the founder of the party. During the protest, FPM leader [[Gebran Bassil]] made a personal statement for the first time in over 13 days.<ref>{{Cite news|title=FPM supporters gather in support of President|url=https://en.annahar.com/article/1061298-fpm-supporters-gather-in-support-of-president|date=3 November 2019|access-date=22 November 2019|publisher=[[An-Nahar]]}}</ref> Bassil claimed \"We should block roads for MPs who refuse corruption-combating laws, politicians who escape accountability and judges who do not implement the law.\" He also demanded lifting banking secrecy on political officials' accounts and insisting accountability, as well as a return of misused or stolen public funds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zawya.com/mena/en/economy/story/Aoun_strategy_risks_delaying_government_formation-SNG_158532276|title=Aoun strategy risks delaying government formation|website=zawya.com|language=en|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref> In the afternoon, tens of thousands of anti-government protesters flooded the streets across Lebanon in a \"Sunday of unity\".<ref>{{cite news |title='Sunday of Unity' rejuvenates protests |url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-04/494939-sunday-of-unity-rejuvenates-protests.ashx |access-date=3 November 2019 |publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> Protesters gathered for the third consecutive Sunday since mass anti-government demonstrations began on 17 October, filling the streets and central squares of major cities including [[Beirut]], [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]] and [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]]. Dozens of main roads were closed by burning tires, mounts of sand and by the sheer amount of protesters, despite an ongoing threat of violence from political-party opposition. Acts of violence from party rivals consisted around Lebanon, such as the attacks on protesters in Beirut blocking public roads.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tens of thousands march in Lebanon's Sunday of Unity |url=http://yalibnan.com/2019/11/04/tens-of-thousands-march-in-lebanons-sunday-of-unity/ |access-date=3 November 2019 |publisher=Ya Libnan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lebanese Keep Protest Alive |url=http://www.naharnet.com/stories/en/266071-lebanese-keep-protest-alive-in-northern-city-of-tripoli |access-date=3 November 2019 |publisher=Naharnet}}</ref> These attacks were presumed to be affiliated with Hezbollah.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/hezbollah-supporters-attack-beirut-protest-site-1.8054380|title=Hezbollah Supporters Attack Beirut Protest Site|date=29 October 2019|work=Haaretz|access-date=4 November 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA candle-light vigil was held on 4 November in [[Baalbek]] in memorial of those who have perished in the Lebanese protest,<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1191408219270332416|user=akhbaralsaha|title=\u0645\u0633\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0634\u0645\u0648\u0639 \u0637\u0627\u0644\u062a \u0633\u0648\u0642 #\u0628\u0639\u0644\u0628\u0643 \u0639\u0646 \u0631\u0648\u062d \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0647\u062f\u0627\u0621 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062b\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0629 #\u0643\u0644\u0646_\u064a\u0639\u0646\u064a_\u0643\u0644\u0646 #\u0627\u062e\u0628\u0627\u0631_\u0627\u0644\u0633\u0627\u062d\u0629 #\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646_\u064a\u0646\u062a\u0641\u0636 #\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646pic.twitter.com/lrSaPuuztH|date=4 November 2019}}</ref> while physical tensions from road blocking persisted in Beirut.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Lebanon's Anti-Government Protesters Call for General Strike|url=https://clicklancashire.com/2019/11/04/lebanon-s-anti-government-protesters-call-for-general-strike.html|date=4 November 2019|access-date=22 November 2019|publisher=Click Lancashire}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 November, some students of [[American University of Science and Technology]] in Beirut showed attendance in protest, and were met with harsh engagement from soldiers of the [[Lebanese Armed Forces]]. [[General Directorate of General Security]] officers were recorded verbally threatening students that were recording the protests.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=Beirutiyat|number=1191666721175851008|title=\u0627\u0644\u062c\u064a\u0634 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645 \u064a\u062d\u0627\u0648\u0644 \u0641\u062a\u062d \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u0629 AUST \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0648\u0629 \u0648\u064a\u0648\u0627\u062c\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0644\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0645\u064a\u064a\u0646 #\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646_\u064a\u0646\u062a\u0641\u0636pic.twitter.com/4WFxE35VZB|date=5 November 2019}}</ref> Protesters in [[Nabatieh]], shut down companies such as [[Ogero|OGERO]], [[Liban Post]], [[Banque du Liban]] and several banks{{source needed|date=March 2020}} despite state-exerted political pressure towards the protesters in this region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the961.com/news/nabatieh-under-constant-duress-and-the-protection-of-the-lebanese-army|title=Nabatieh Under Constant Duress and the Protection of the Lebanese Army|website=the961.com|language=en-us|access-date=5 November 2019}}</ref> Protesters were present outside electrical company buildings, frustrated with decades of inconsistent power and common outages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191105-electricity-water-cuts-power-lebanon-s-protest-movement|title=Electricity, water cuts power Lebanon's protest movement|website=[[France 24]]|language=en-us|access-date=11 November 2019|date=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThousands of students across Lebanon protested on 6 November in front of universities and schools refusing to attend classes until their demands are met.<ref>{{cite news |title=Thousands of students protest on 21st day of uprising |url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-06/495088-thousands-of-sidon-students-protest-on-21st-day-of-uprising.ashx |access-date=6 November 2019 |publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> Several student led movements have been organized since the start of the protests, in demand of a financial student contract, the reversal of the decision to change tuition fees to the dollar currency in some universities, independent student councils in each university, and a well-funded Lebanese University. On the national scale, they have been asking for social, political, and economic reform, in hopes of finding respectable job prospects after graduation without nepotism or sect bias. Pension and retirement plans are also being demanded, as well as proper health care coverage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/lebanon-students-skip-school-protesters-eye-state-institutions-191106131406319.html|title=Lebanon students skip school as protesters eye state institutions|website=[[Al Jazeera]]|language=en-us|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> In the afternoon, protesters began to gradually grow across Lebanon and started protesting by the thousands in front of key governmental and private institutions and forced some of them to close their doors.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lebanon protesters seek to shut down key state institutions |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/lebanon-protesters-seek-shut-state-institutions-191106071921890.html |access-date=6 November 2019 |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Fourth week: 8\u201314 November ===\nIt was reported on 9 November 2019 that the dollar-rationing policies implemented by Lebanese banks were at risk of causing major shortages and price hikes in gasoline, petrol, food and other vital supplies. Suleiman Haroun, the head of the Lebanese Syndicate of Hospitals, said that medical stocks in the country \"will not last more than a month\" unless a solution is found.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fuel shortage, price hikes squeeze protest-hit Lebanon|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191109-fuel-shortage-price-hikes-squeeze-protest-hit-lebanon|access-date=11 November 2019|publisher=[[France 24]]}}</ref> During the weekend, news spread of a planned parliamentary legislative session on 12 November that would include a proposed general amnesty law, which could grant current and past members protection against prosecution for crimes such as corruption and misuse of public funds. In response, protesters called for a general strike to be held on the same day, and published a list of demands which included bolstering guarantees for a speedy trial, working towards a solution for the economic crisis, guaranteeing the independence of the judiciary and investigating the misuse of public funds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Protesters to Oppose Tuesday's Parliamentary Session with a Widespread Strike|url=https://www.the961.com/news/protesters-to-oppose-tuesdays-parliamentary-session-with-a-widespread-strike|access-date=11 November 2019 |publisher=The961}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Politicians eye amnesty to quell street pressure|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-07/495135-politicians-eye-amnesty-to-quell-street-pressure.ashx|access-date=11 November 2019 |publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Flare_shines_light_in_group_of_passionate_Lebanese_protesters.jpg|thumb|left|Flare shines light in group of protesters. [[Beirut]], 10 November 2019]]\nOn 11 November, the Lebanese Federation of Syndicates of Bank Employees called for a general strike for its 11,000 members over \"concerns for safety\". This strike is unprecedented in the country's history and its impact is unclear. No end date was specified for the strike, and a general closure of all Lebanese banks may very well be the result.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lebanese bank employee union calls strike over safety concerns|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-protests-banks/lebanese-bank-employee-union-calls-strike-over-safety-concerns-idUSKBN1XL19U|access-date=11 November 2019 |publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> [[Riad Salameh]], the governor of Lebanon's [[central bank]] ([[Banque du Liban]]) gave a press conference in which he denied the possibility of capital control on the Lebanese economy, assured that a \"haircut\" on large accounts is not a possibility, and repeated that the central bank's priority remains on economic stability and confidence in the Lebanese Pound. When asked about the strike by the bank staff union announced earlier in the day, Salameh claimed to have not yet heard of it.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lebanon central bank says bank deposits are safe, banks to review curbs|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-protests-salameh/lebanons-central-bank-says-deposits-secure-will-preserve-stable-pound-idUSKBN1XL1DN|access-date=11 November 2019 |publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> A few minutes after Salameh's press conference, Speaker of Parliament [[Nabih Berri]] appeared on live television to announce that the following day's parliamentary session had been delayed until 19 November 2019, possibly as a response to protests called for during the weekend against the proposed general amnesty bill that was due to be discussed. Berri claimed the postponement was for \"security reasons\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Tuesday's legislative session postponed for security reasons|url=https://en.annahar.com/article/1066188-tuesdays-legislative-session-postponed-for-security-reasons|access-date=11 November 2019 |publisher=[[An-Nahar]]}}</ref> In the afternoon, Hezbollah Secretary General Hassan Nasrallah gave a speech in which he made strong overtures towards a corruption investigation to be led by Lebanon's judiciary, offering for Hezbollah to collaborate fully with any such investigation and calling for a \"strong, independent judiciary\" to equally investigate all Lebanese parties without reservation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nasrallah says Hezbollah is ready to cooperate with the judiciary on any corruption case involving its members|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-11/495351-nasrallah-says-hezbollah-is-ready-to-cooperate-with-the-judiciary-on-any-corruption-case-involving.ashx|access-date=11 November 2019 |publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> Nasrallah also called for banking secrecy and any prior amnesty for public representatives to be lifted, \"dating back to 1992\".\n\nOn 12 November, speaker of Parliament [[Nabih Berri]] was reported to have sent resigned Prime Minister [[Saad Hariri]] a pot of [[Leben (milk product)|Leben]], a traditional Lebanese dairy product, along with a note that promised \"eternal enmity\" if Hariri refused to form a new government. Hariri thanked Berri for the Leben but excused himself as having ceased eating all kinds of milks and cheeses due to [[lactose intolerance]], concluding that \"indeed, the state of the country itself requires a new political diet or \"regime\", so to speak\". The unusual exchange was covered in Lebanese media.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u064a\u0631\u064a \u064a\u0639\u0644\u0651\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0643\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0628\u0631\u0651\u064a \u0641\u064a \"\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0647\u0627\u0631\": \"\u0645\u062a\u0648\u0642\u0651\u0641 \u0639\u0646 \u062a\u0646\u0627\u0648\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0644\u0628\u0627\u0646 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u062c\u0628\u0627\u0646\"|url=https://www.annahar.com/article/1066728-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%8A-%D9%8A%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%82-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%83%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%B1%D9%8A-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D9%85%D8%AA%D9%88%D9%82%D9%81-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%AA%D9%86%D8%A7%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%86-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%AC%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%86|access-date=12 November 2019|publisher=[[An-Nahar]]}}</ref> President [[Michel Aoun]] gave a live interview at 8:30PM, during which he rejected calls for a fully [[technocratic]] government, warned against a [[run on the bank]] further damaging the economic sector, and called for an immediate end to the protests to prevent a \"catastrophe\". Aoun accused protesters of \"stabbing the nation with a dagger\" and accused protesters that blocked roads of \"violating international law\". Aoun also stated that \"anyone who cannot find faith in the current Lebanese government can leave Lebanon and live somewhere else\".<ref>{{cite AV media|date=12 November 2019|title=Lebanese President Aoun gives live interview amid crisis|location=Lebanon|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wE3Hpukid2U|publisher=News Alert}}</ref> Aoun's interview proved exceedingly unpopular with the protest movement, which began blocking an unprecedented number of arterial roads in Beirut and across Lebanon before the interview was even concluded including Qob Elias,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194336163365937155 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0645\u062d\u0644\u0629 \u0645\u0641\u0631\u0642 #\u0642\u0628_\u0627\u0644\u064a\u0627\u0633 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0634\u062a\u0639\u0644\u0629}}</ref> \"Ring Bridge\",<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194338303945904128 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u062a\u0642\u0627\u0637\u0639 #\u0628\u0631\u062c_\u0627\u0644\u063a\u0632\u0627\u0644 \u0628\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647 #\u062c\u0633\u0631_\u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0646\u063a}}</ref> Dahr el Baidar,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194339035717808128 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 #\u0636\u0647\u0631_\u0627\u0644\u0628\u064a\u062f\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0644\u0629 #\u062c\u062f\u064a\u062a\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u064a}}</ref> Jiyyeh,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194344105809268737 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0648\u062a\u0648\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0627\u062f #\u0627\u0644\u062c\u064a\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0644\u0629 \u0645\u0641\u0631\u0642 #\u0628\u0631\u062c\u0627}}</ref> Nahr el Kalb,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194347573710077955 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0648\u062a\u0648\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0627\u062f #\u0646\u0647\u0631_\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0644\u0628 \u0628\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647 #\u062c\u0648\u0646\u064a\u0629}}</ref> Neemeh,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194349561755656193 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0631 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0648\u062a\u0648\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0627\u062f #\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0639\u0645\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646}}</ref> Beddawi,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194352199255678976 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0648\u062a\u0648\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0627\u062f #\u0627\u0644\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0648\u064a \u0648 #\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646}}</ref> Abdeh, Mahmara, Braqil,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194352651959521281 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0645\u062d\u0644\u0629 \u0633\u0627\u062d\u0629 #\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0629 \u060c #\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062d\u0645\u0631\u0629 \u060c \u0645\u0641\u0631\u0642 #\u0627\u0644\u0628\u064a\u0627\u062f\u0631 \u0648\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0627\u0645 #\u0628\u0631\u0642\u0627\u064a\u0644 #\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0647 \u0645\u062d\u0644\u0629 \u0628\u0631\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628}}</ref> Madina Riyadiyya,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194352940674367489 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u062a\u0642\u0627\u0637\u0639 #\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u064a\u0646\u0629_\u0627\u0644\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636\u064a\u0629}}</ref> Verdun,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194353267297390592 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0645\u062d\u0644\u0629 \u0634\u0627\u0631\u0639 #\u0641\u0631\u062f\u0627\u0646}}</ref> Jal el Dib,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194354020359528449 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0648\u062a\u0648\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0627\u062f #\u062c\u0644_\u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0628 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646}}</ref> Hasbaya,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194355028598890496 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0627\u0645 #\u062d\u0627\u0635\u0628\u064a\u0627 \u0645\u062d\u0644\u0629 #\u0633\u0648\u0642_\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0627\u0646}}</ref> the Palma highway,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194355584033787905 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0648\u062a\u0648\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0627\u062f #\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646}}</ref> Aley,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194356436031008768 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0645\u0633\u062a\u062f\u064a\u0631\u0629 #\u0639\u0627\u0644\u064a\u0647}}</ref> Cola,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194375588435365888 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u062c\u0633\u0631 #\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u0644\u0627 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646}}</ref> Dawra,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194387018756894720 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u062c\u0633\u0631 #\u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646}}</ref> Sayyfi,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194399541132451840 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u062a\u0642\u0627\u0637\u0639 #\u0627\u0644\u0635\u064a\u0641\u064a #\u0628\u064a\u0631\u0648\u062a}}</ref> Corniche al Mazraa,<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194366629687283712 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0639\u0644\u0649 #\u0643\u0648\u0631\u0646\u064a\u0634_\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0632\u0631\u0639\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0627\u062a\u062c\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0646}}</ref> and Sassine.<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=tmclebanon |number=1194363547679166466 |date =12 November 2019|title=\u0642\u0637\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0645\u062d\u0644\u0629 \u0633\u0627\u062d\u0629 #\u0633\u0627\u0633\u064a\u0646}}</ref> Alaa Abou Fakhr,<ref name=\"An-Nahar\" /> a Lebanese national, was shot and killed in [[Khalde]] at the ensuing protests.\n\nProtesters began appearing in the early morning of 13 November near the heavily fortified [[Baabda Palace|Baabda Presidential Palace]] to express dissatisfaction with President Aoun's speech a few hours earlier, and picked up in pace as the day progressed.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=lbci_news|number=1194404313008873475|date=12 November 2019|title=\u0648\u0635\u0648\u0644 \u0639\u062f\u062f \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u0638\u0627\u0647\u0631\u064a\u0646 \u0644\u0644\u0627\u0639\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0645 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0645\u0642\u0631\u0628\u0629 \u0645\u0646 \u0637\u0631\u064a\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0635\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062c\u0645\u0647\u0648\u0631\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0628\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627}}</ref>\n\nActivist and protester Khaldoun Jaber was released on 14 November after being detained by the Lebanese army in [[Baabda]] the previous day in mysterious circumstances. Jaber was shown to have marks of physical abuse upon his release, which he claimed were due to torture by the army during his detention. Jaber also claimed to have been exposed to psychological abuse.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=MTVEnglishNews|number=1194972536548790272|date=14 November 2019|title=Activist Khaldoun Jaber after his release: They tried to expose me by using psychological intimidation techniques and through investigation #LebanonProtests}}</ref> During his detention, Jaber was not given access to a lawyer with even the location of his detention being kept secret. The reason for his arrest was unclear, with some sources claiming it was due to attempting to cross a security perimeter during the previous day's protest near [[Baabda Palace]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Khaldoun Jaber, arr\u00eat\u00e9 \u00e0 Baabda et d\u00e9tenu dans des circonstances obscures, a \u00e9t\u00e9 rel\u00e2ch\u00e9|url=https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/1195004/manifestation-a-baabda-mobilisation-pour-la-liberation-dun-libanais-arrete-dans-des-circonstances-floues.html|access-date=14 November 2019|publisher=[[L'Orient Le Jour]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Fifth week: 15\u201321 November ===\nAs the protests continue nationwide, Sleiman Haroun, the president of the Syndicate of Private Hospitals, threatened to have 15 November 2019 as a day of closure to all patients except the ones who have dialysis, chemotherapy treatment and emergency care, unless some immediate action is taken by the authorities in the government.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-08/495219-hospitals-to-strike-next-friday-over-states-nonpayment.ashx|title=Hospitals to strike next Friday over state's nonpayment {{!}} News , Lebanon News {{!}} THE DAILY STAR|website=dailystar.com.lb|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> Haroun said the strike has nothing to do with the current protest and his purpose was to \"raise awareness\" and highlight the fact that the government has not been paying its full dues to the hospitals since 2011 and owes them a total of $1.3 billion as of today.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-16/495700-private-hospitals-stage-warning-strike-over-late-payments.ashx|title=Private hospitals stage 'warning strike' over late payments {{!}} News , Lebanon News {{!}} THE DAILY STAR|website=dailystar.com.lb|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> Since no direct response was received, all hospitals in Metn, Akkar and Nabatieh areas went on strike that day; doctors along with the hospital\u2019s medical teams and staff were on the streets \"breathing their last breath\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-15/495644-private-hospitals-close-doors-for-one-day-strike.ashx|title=Private hospitals close doors for one-day strike over govt nonpayment {{!}} News , Lebanon News {{!}} THE DAILY STAR|website=dailystar.com.lb|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nCurrency and payment issues are causing additional burden on hospitals. Hospitals are running out of medical supplies and equipment, because they are 100% reliant on imported supplies and equipment.<ref name=\":0\" /> Due to shortage of US currency in Lebanon, banks have not been able to transfer fund in US dollar to the companies who import these supplies.<ref name=\":0\" /> Suppliers now have to turn to exchange houses in order to get their US dollars, which end up charging significantly higher rates than the official rate of 1$ to 1,507.5 L.L., only if they had any dollars to sell.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-09/495271-hit-by-slew-of-problems-hospitals-threaten-strike.ashx|title=Hit by slew of problems, hospitals threaten strike {{!}} News , Lebanon News {{!}} THE DAILY STAR|website=dailystar.com.lb|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> Suppliers have also not been paid by the hospitals as a result of the situation. If this continues, hospitals will only have one month before they run out of their current shelf stock.<ref name=\":0\" /> Hospitals have received no payment since the beginning of 2019 and salary reductions are being considered in many hospitals if the situation does not improve.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBeirut Bar Association elections were held on 17 November. The independent candidate, Melhem Khalaf, won the majority vote (2,341 votes) to become the BBA's Council president and the first independent candidate to win against politically affiliated candidates in decades. Khalaf's contenders were Nader Gaspard, Saadeddine Al Khatib, and Ibrahim Moussallem. Pierre Hanna, who was backed by the [[Lebanese Forces]], [[Progressive Socialist Party]] and the [[Future Movement]], as well as twelve other candidates either dropped out or were not voted in, competed for council positions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-17/495743-beirut-bar-association-elects-new-head-councilmembers.ashx|title=Independent Melhem Khalaf voted head of Beirut Bar Association|date=17 November 2019|access-date=22 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref>[[File:WomenLine RiadElSolh 19Nov2019.jpg|thumb|Women protesters forming a line between riot police and protesters in Riad el Solh, [[Beirut]]; 19 November 2019]]Parliament was set to hold two sessions in the morning of 19 November, including a legislative session that was opposed by protesters, due to it timetabling a controversial amnesty law that was perceived as potentially granting amnesty to crimes committed by the political class, such as misappropriation of public funds or corruption. The sessions were originally planned for 12 November, but were already once postponed due to protests. 58 out of 128 Members of Parliament were boycotting the session, but that number was not sufficient to prevent quorum. A human chain was planned around the Lebanese Parliament to prevent Members of Parliament from entering the premises and to thereby force the session to be postponed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Protesters plan human chain to block Parliament sessions|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-19/495885-protesters-plan-human-chain-to-block-parliament-sessions.ashx|access-date=19 November 2019|date=19 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> Protesters began gathering early in the morning. Convoys for some Members of Parliament were recorded shooting live bullets or speeding into crowds in an attempt to disperse protesters.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=chehayebk|number=1196692730983931905|date=19 November 2019|title=An MP's convoy of 3 cars tries to drive past protestors blocking the road, who then try to stop the car & throw bottles and other small objects. One bodyguard opens the window & shoots warning shots into the air -- then appears to detour. (Video via an eyewitness)}}</ref> Many protesters were gravely injured. At around 11:20am, Secretary General of the Lebanese Parliament [[Adnane Daher]] confirmed to local media that both parliament sessions were postponed indefinitely. This was perceived as a victory by protesters.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lebanon parliament postpones session as protesters block roads|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/lebanon-parliament-postpones-session-protesters-block-roads-191119084939933.html|access-date=19 November 2019|date=19 November 2019|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> Lebanese banks reopened for the first time since 11 November after the Lebanese Federation of Syndicates of Bank Employees ended its strike.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lebanese line up as banks reopen|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-19/495903-lebanese-line-up-as-banks-reopen.ashx|access-date=19 November 2019|date=19 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref>\n\nPresident [[Michel Aoun]] gave a speech on 21 November, on the eve of [[Lebanese Independence Day]], in which he called for an end to protests and \"hateful language on the streets\" and promised an \"anti-corruption cabinet\". Protesters expressed dissatisfaction with the speech by resuming the closing of roads.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-22/496094-aoun-promises-anti-corruption-cabinet.ashx|title=Aoun promises anti-corruption Cabinet|date=22 November 2019|access-date=22 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Sixth week: 22\u201328 November ===\n[[File:Lebanon IdependenceDay 2019.jpg|thumb|Protests in the evening of Lebanon's 76th Independence Day celebration in Martyr's Square, Beirut.]]\nLebanon's 76th [[Lebanese Independence Day|Independence Day]] was celebrated on 22 November 2019 with the nation's first-ever civil parade, which was organized by civil society groups in Beirut's Martyr's Square. An invite-only private military parade had been held in the early morning by the Lebanese government, and the civil parade was intended as a rebuke against the government organized by the \"true Lebanese\": the parade had \"batallions\" representing different groups from Lebanese society, including cooks, schoolteachers, retired military personnel, pharmacists, engineers, women's rights activists, bankers, athletes, performance artists and more. The civil parade coincided with a program of festival activities organized by independent groups, which included dancing and heat lantern lighting. Marches were held across the Beirut region in the morning, all arriving to the civil parade in central Beirut.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Defiant protesters hold rival parade on Lebanon independence day|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/defiant-protesters-hold-rival-parade-lebanon-independence-day-191122202937296.html|date=23 November 2019|access-date=23 November 2019|first=Timour|last=Azhari|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Diverse Lebanon protesters unite to celebrate 'real' independence day|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/diverse-lebanon-protesters-unite-to-celebrate-real-independence-day/|date=23 November 2019|access-date=23 November 2019|first1=Layal|last1=Abou Rahal|first2=Guillaume|last2=Klein|publisher=[[The Times of Israel]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Lebanese citizens take to the streets to celebrate Independence Day|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/lebanese-citizens-take-to-the-streets-to-celebrate-independence-day-1.941282|date=23 November 2019|access-date=23 November 2019||publisher=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 November, five youths, including children aged 12 and 15, were detained by Lebanese military intelligence after taking down a banner which supported the [[Free Patriotic Movement]], which is the party of President Aoun. Their detention was reported to the media by their families, and the children were released past midnight after the intervention of volunteer lawyers.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Five released after arrest for tearing down FPM banner|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-24/496149-five-released-after-arrest-for-tearing-down-fpm-banner.ashx|date=24 November 2019|access-date=23 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref>\n\nA protest was held on 24 November outside the United States embassy in Lebanon to express opposition to U.S. interference in Lebanon. The protest came after [[Hezbollah]] accused the United States in meddling with and delaying the formation of a new cabinet, and after comments made by U.S. ambassador [[Jeffrey Feltman]] in which he said that \"reactions to [Hezbollah] by Lebanese leaders and institutions fortunately coincide with U.S. interests\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Hezbollah accuses US of meddling in Lebanon's crisis|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-22/496122-hezbollah-accuses-us-of-meddling-in-lebanons-crisis.ashx|date=23 November 2019|access-date=24 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Scores protest foreign interference outside U.S. Embassy|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-24/496151-scores-protest-foreign-interference-outside-us-embassy.ashx|date=24 November 2019|access-date=24 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> Around noon, another protest was held across the Lebanese coastline to draw attention to the high level of environmental pollution in Lebanon.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Uprising day 39: Protesters reclaim the coast|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-24/496150-day-39-protesters-take-to-sea-to-highlight-environment.ashx|access-date=24 November 2019|date=24 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> Right before midnight, pro-government [[Hezbollah]] and [[Amal Movement]] supporters violently clashed with protesters in the \"Ring\" bridge and Jal el Dib areas, demanding an end to road blocks imposed by protesters. This came after protesters apparently physically assaulted two people after suspecting them of being Hezbollah supporters.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=timourazhari|number=1198693907804164096|date=25 November 2019|title=It seems a couple people were beaten because they were suspected of being Hezbollah supporters. Here, 2 or 3 men chant in support of Nasrallah, protesters respond with \u201call of them means all of them.\u201d Then they sing the national anthem.}}</ref> The Hezbollah/Amal supporters burned civil society tents, trashed cars and caused damage to public and private property. The Lebanese army intervened with tear gas and flash grenades hours later, dispersing one of the most violent evenings since the beginning of the protests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/lebanon-protesters-hezbollah-amal-supporters-clash-beirut-191125024849508.html|title=Lebanon protesters and Hezbollah, Amal supporters clash in Beirut|access-date=25 November 2019|date=25 November 2019|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=timourazhari|number=1198789793934651397|title=More of the aftermath from downtown #Beirut. Several cars destroyed and torched, but damage to tents is limited. People here saying they stood their ground and fought back.|date=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hezbollah Amal 25Nov2019.jpg|thumb|left|Hezbollah and Amal Movement supporters arrive to Martyr's Square on motorbikes. 25 November 2019.]]\nAt around noon on 25 November, Hussein Chalhoub and his sister-in-law Sanaa al-Jundi died after their car hit a makeshift roadblock used by protesters to cut off access to the Jiyyeh highway. This inflamed tensions between protesters and pro-government [[Hezbollah]]/[[Amal Movement]] supporters.<ref name=\"dailystar.com.lb\" /> [[J\u00e1n Kubi\u0161]], the [[United Nations]] Special Coordinator for Lebanon, issued multiple statements on Twitter warning against escalating confrontation between protesters and Hezbollah/Amal Movement supporters.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1198941030487384065|user=unjankubis|title=1/2The attack of last night of groups under Hizbullah & Amal flags on demonstrators again exposed how dangerous are such actions of political activists, how easily they can  trigger confrontation, even sectarian ones, how challenging it is for security forces to protect law and..|date=25 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=unjankubis|number=1198941031833702400|title=2/2 ...order. I urge all Lebanese political forces to control their supporters, to avoid using the national protests for pursuing their political agenda #Lebanon|date=25 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=unjankubis|number=1199026037444796416|date=25 November 2019|title=The tragedy this morning that took the life of 2 civilians & injured their child is a warning. Road blockages that take lives of innocent people, paralyze economy & could trigger confrontation could only compromise peaceful protests & their legitimate demand 4 reforms & change}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=unjankubis|number=1199046486895603712|date=25 November 2019|title=Provoking each-other by violent acts and foul words of hatred is a dangerous path that could lead to confrontation and conflict #Lebanon}}</ref> Later in the afternoon, pro-government Hezbollah and Amal Movement supporters began roving around Beirut, Tyre and other cities on mopeds and motorbikes, shouting taunts and provocations at protesters. Some physical clashes ensued, and the confrontations continued to occur sporadically until later in the evening.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2007781/lebanon-protesters-defiant-despite-hezbollah-amal-attack|title=Lebanon Protesters Defiant Despite Hezbollah, Amal Attack|access-date=26 November 2019|date=25 November 2019|publisher=[[Asharq Al-Awsat]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/night-clashes-lebanon-anti-gov-protests-191126062640907.html|title=Second night of clashes in Lebanon amid anti-gov't protests|date=26 November 2019|access-date=26 November 2019|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\nResigned Prime Minister [[Saad Hariri]] formally announced on 26 November that he would not run again for the position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-protests-hariri/lebanons-hariri-says-he-does-not-want-be-pm-idUSKBN1Y01JN|title=Lebanon's Hariri says he does not want be PM|date=26 November 2019|access-date=26 November 2019|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> Meanwhile, businessman [[Samir Khatib]] announced that he was \"ready to form a new government\", and seemed to accrue some level of endorsement from political parties.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Samir Khatib says ready to form a govt|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-26/496301-samir-khatib-says-ready-to-form-a-govt.ashx|date=26 November 2019|access-date=26 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> President [[Michel Aoun]] announced that binding consultations to designate a new Prime Minister would be held on 28 November.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Aoun to hold consultations for new PM on Thursday: Source|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-26/496292-aoun-to-hold-consultations-thursday-for-new-pm-source.ashx|date=26 November 2019|access-date=26 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> Overnight, clashes occurred all around Lebanon. In [[Baalbek]], Hezbollah/Amal Movement supporters destroyed protester's tents and also their sound system.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=chehayebk|number=1199364194828783616|title=It appears that protestors camped out in #Baalbek had their camps demolished by partisans holding Hezbollah and Amal flags chanting \"Shia, Shia\". #Lebanon Army visible forming what could be a line b/w protestors the partisans.|date=26 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=LunaSafwan|number=1199642866462679040|title=#Hezbollah & Amal supporters trashed the protestors' sound system, threatened them and also cornered most of them in an office around the street where army officers served as a buffer front to protect protestors in #Baalbak #Lebanon #LebanonProtests|date=27 November 2019}}</ref> In [[Bikfaya]], [[Free Patriotic Movement]] (the party of sitting President [[Michel Aoun]]) supporters organized a protest in front of the home of former President [[Amin Gemayel]]. They clashed with [[Kataeb Party]] (Gemayel's party) supporters, which led to injuries and the destruction of private property until the Lebanese army intervened.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.naharnet.com/stories/en/266740|title=Confrontation between FPM, Kataeb Supporters in Bikfaya|date=26 November 2019|access-date=27 November 2019|publisher=[[Naharnet]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Lebanon Clashes Threaten to Crack Open Fault Lines|url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2008681/lebanon-clashes-threaten-crack-open-fault-lines|access-date=26 November 2019|date=26 November 2019|publisher=[[Asharq Al-Awsat]]}}</ref> Clashes also occurred in [[Chyah]] and Ein Rummaneh. The [[Lebanese Red Cross]] claimed that dozens of people were injured including one female FPM activist injured to the head,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.lbcgroup.tv/news/d/lebanon-news/485460/kataeb-supporters-lob-stones-at-fpm-supporters-in/en |title = Kataeb supporters lob stones at FPM supporters in Bikfaya, one injury reported \u2013&#91;VIDEOS&#93;}}</ref> while the Lebanese army said that at least 16 people were detained for their involvement in the clashes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7104073dd7544dcd88ca7185e92bf882|title=Overnight clashes in Lebanon injure dozens as tensions rise|first1=Bassem|last1=Mroue|date=27 November 2019|access-date=27 November 2019|publisher=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 November, Lebanon's Syndicate of Gas Station Owners announced that an open-ended strike would begin the next day to highlight the \"size of the losses sustained by the sector due to the presence of two dollar [rates] in the Lebanese market.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=Gas station owners announce open-ended strike from Thursday|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-27/496380-gas-station-owners-announce-open-ended-strike-from-thursday.ashx|date=27 November 2019|access-date=28 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> Hundreds of Lebanese mothers led a \"mother's march\" in [[Chyah]] to protest against sectarian violence on 26 November between youths.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Mothers lead march between Muslim-Christian suburbs|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-28/496410-mothers-lead-march-between-muslim-christian-suburbs.ashx|date=28 November 2019|access-date=28 November 2019|first1=Timour|last1=Azhari|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref>\n\nSources at the Lebanese Ministry of Finance claimed to local media that the Lebanese Central Bank was scheduled to repay US$1.5 billion in Eurobond debt which matures on 28 November, putting to rest speculation that Lebanon could default on its debt. However, Lebanon still has outstanding Eurobond debt due in 2020, and media sources noted that the path towards refinancing necessary to handle that debt is unclear without a cabinet.<ref>{{Cite news|title='No default': Lebanon ready to settle $1.5B Eurobond|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/Business/Local/2019/Nov-28/496420-no-default-lebanon-ready-to-settle-15b-eurobond.ashx|first1=Osama|last1=Habib|date=28 November 2019|access-date=28 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/c93ebf3293ca4b0f868de4595c33310e|title=Fear, turmoil in Lebanon as its financial crisis worsens|first1=Bassem|last1=Mroue|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|date=21 November 2019|access-date=28 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/Business/Local/2019/Nov-28/496435-lebanon-pays-15b-eurobond-finance-ministry-source.ashx|title=Lebanon pays $1.5B Eurobond: Finance Ministry source|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|access-date=28 November 2019|date=28 November 2019}}</ref> A protest occurred in front of the Lebanese Central Bank and other government administrative and judiciary institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-28/496426-day-43-protest-at-vat-building-sidon-schools-locked.ashx|title=Day 43: Protests at VAT building, Central Bank|date=28 November 2019|access-date=29 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> [[Arab League]] ambassador [[Hossam Zaki]] formally expressed \"readiness\" to help solve the political and economic crisis in Lebanon for the first time since the beginning of the protests.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Arab League Says Ready to Help Solve Lebanon Crisis|url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2012161/arab-league-says-ready-help-solve-lebanon-crisis|publisher=[[Asharq Al-Awsat]]|date=28 November 2019|access-date=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Seventh week: 29 November \u2013 5 December ===\nOn 29 November 2019, protests occurred in front of the Lebanese Central Bank and some other judiciary and administrative government buildings and institutions, with the aim of preventing public sector employees from entering these institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-29/496486-uprising-day-44-protesters-continue-to-gather-outside-state-institutions.ashx|title=Uprising day 44: Protesters gather outside state institutions|date=29 November 2019|access-date=29 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> Multiple media sources claimed that [[Hezbollah]] had asked President [[Michel Aoun]] to delay binding parliamentary consultations, which were scheduled for 28 November, under the hope that resigned Prime Minister [[Saad Hariri]] would revert his decision not to lead the next cabinet.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.naharnet.com/stories/en/266820-report-hizbullah-asks-aoun-to-postpone-consultations|title=Report: Hizbullah Asks Aoun to 'Postpone' Consultations|publisher=[[Naharnet]]|date=29 November 2019|access-date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first1=Nazir|last1=Rida|url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2013371/lebanon-hezbollah-asks-aoun-postpone-consultations-try-persuade-hariri|title=Lebanon: 'Hezbollah' Asks Aoun to Postpone Consultations to Try Persuade Hariri|date=29 November 2019|access-date=29 November 2019|publisher=[[Asharq Al-Awsat]]}}</ref>\n\nProtesters gathered on 3 December across the country in response to businessman Samir Khatib's nomination as possible new prime minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/lebanon-s-protesters-unimpressed-by-proposals-for-next-prime-minister-1.946824|title=Lebanon's protestors unimpressed by proposaals for next prime minister|date=3 December 2019|access-date=4 December 2019|publisher=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]}}</ref> Several cases of [[suicide]] were being linked to deteriorating living conditions in Lebanon, most prominently the death of 40-year old Naji Fleity in [[Arsal]]. According to local media, Fleity committed suicide because he was unable to provide for his family after losing his job. His suicide sparked a large outcry of anger online.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/lebanon-suicide-of-indebted-father-sparks-anger-as-economic-woes-grow-1.946098|title=Lebanon: Suicide of indebted father sparks anger as economic woes grow|date=3 December 2019|access-date=4 December 2019|publisher=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]}}</ref>\n\nProtesters resumed blocking roads on 4 December following politicians' apparent consensus on designating Samir Khatib as the next prime minister.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-04/496779-roads-blocked-after-political-consensus-on-khatib.ashx|title=Roads blocked after political consensus on Khatib|date=4 December 2019|access-date=4 December 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Eighth week: 6\u201312 December ===\nOn 7 December 2019, about a thousand people marched in [[Beirut]] to protest [[sexual harassment]] in Lebanon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-07/497005-march-against-sexual-harassment-in-beirut.ashx|title=March against sexual harassment in Beirut|date=7 December 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> A man [[Self-immolation|self-immolated]] during the protest and survived, with his motives being unclear.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/world/lebanese-women-march-in-beirut-against-sexual-harassment-1.4719908|title=Lebanese women march in Beirut against sexual harassment|date=8 December 2019|publisher=[[CTV News]]}}</ref> The protest came after days of prolonged controversy surrounding a personal trainer in Beirut who was accused by over fifty women of sexual misconduct.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://stepfeed.com/marwan-you-ve-been-all-but-habib-to-lebanese-women-no-proof-needed-0619|title=Marwan, you've been all but Habib to Lebanese women, no proof needed|date=3 December 2019|publisher=StepFeed}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-04/496763-lawyer-files-suit-against-alleged-serial-harasser-after-numerous-women-step-forward.ashx|title=Lawyer files suit against alleged serial harasser after numerous women step forward|date=4 December 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref>\n\nReports of women journalists being attacked also began to surface around this time. [[The Coalition For Women In Journalism]], which has a special focus on women journalists, documented several attacks. \"Covering large protests in many parts of the Middle East has always been so hard for women journalists \u2014 we remember the many terrible incidents that happened during the Arab Spring. Following which over the years we have seen many journalism support organizations and others in the industry to train and equip women reporters to be able to take precautions on the ground. But the scope of these attacks are now changing and diversifying.\" the organization's founding director Kiran Nazish said. \"Unfortunately this is an ever more precarious situation and it is important to point out to Lebanese authorities that they have a responsibility to protect the press. Not doing so or doing the opposite is rather reckless,\" Kiran added.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://medium.com/the-coalition-for-women-in-journalism/lebanon-safety-of-women-journalists-in-jeopardy-amidst-protests-eee53988e7ee|title=Lebanon safety of women journalists in jeopardy amidst protests|date=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 December, Samir Khatib withdrew as candidate for prime minister after failing to get enough backing from the Sunni Muslim parties in parliament.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/lebanon-crisis-pm-candidate-samir-khatib-withdraws-from-consideration-1.948616|title=Lebanon crisis: PM Candidate Samir Khatib withdraws from consideration|date=9 December 2019|publisher=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]}}</ref> With Khatib's withdrawal, Saad Hariri became the only candidate for prime minister once again. Protesters then gathered outside parliament to condemn Hariri's candidacy and demand an independent candidate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/lebanon-hariri-emerges-pm-candidate-khatib-withdraws-191208192459108.html|title=Lebanon: Hariri emerges as PM candidate, Khatib withdraws|date=9 December 2019|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\nFollowing days of heavy rainfall, a house collapsed on 10 December in [[Tripoli]], killing two adult siblings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.beirut.com/l/59097|title=Aboudi Kakhiyeh Died In Tripoli This Morning 3 Days Before His Engagement|publisher=Beirut.com}}</ref> Protesters, claiming that the house collapsed due to consistent municipal negligence, stormed the Tripoli municipal police office and demonstrated outside the house of the mayor. They smashed windows, set a room on fire, and damaged a car. The army intervened to stop the violence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2019/12/10/world/middleeast/ap-ml-lebanon-protests.html|title=Angry Protesters Attack Lebanese City's Municipality|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> In [[Jounieh]], four protesters were detained after attempting to block roads. They were released the same evening after another protest blocked the Jounieh highway.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lorientlejour.com/article/1198159/quatre-manifestants-arretes-a-laube-a-jounieh-liberes-en-soiree.html|title=Quatre manifestants arr\u00eat\u00e9s \u00e0 l'aube \u00e0 Jounieh, lib\u00e9r\u00e9s en soir\u00e9e|publisher=[[L'Orient Le Jour]]}}</ref> In Beirut, protesters organized demonstrations outside the houses of current and former public works ministers. While attempting to reach the home of former public works and transportation minister [[Ghazi Zaiter]], they were blocked at [[Rue Verdun]] by men dressed in uniforms of the Internal Security Forces. Cars were vandalized as the men dragged protesters out to beat them; a dozen people including reporter Paula Naufal were hospitalized for their injuries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.annahar.com/article/1083628-security-forces-violently-attack-protestors-near-berri-residence|title=Security forces violently attack protestors near Berri residence|publisher=[[An-Nahar]]}}</ref>\n\nProtesters in Tripoli resumed blocking roads on 11 December.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-11/497227-day-56-tripoli-protesters-block-roads.ashx|title=Day 56: Tripoli protesters block roads|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Ninth week: 13\u201319 December ===\nRiot police used [[tear gas]] against groups of men that attacked protesters' camps in Beirut on 14 December 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/street-battles-beirut-counter-protesters-clash-police-191214200718543.html|title=Street battles in Beirut as counterprotesters clash with police|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> In the evening, protesters in [[Beirut Central District|central Beirut]] attempted to reach Nejmeh Square, chanting slogans against Saad Hariri, who was expected to be named Prime Minister by Monday, and Gebran Bassil. The protesters were met with violence, tear gas and rubber bullets by the Lebanese internal security forces.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2314790-traangas-en-rubberen-kogels-gebruikt-tegen-demonstranten-beiroet.html|title=Traangas en rubberen kogels gebruikt tegen demonstranten Beiroet|publisher=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-14/497447-security-forces-fire-tear-gas-rubber-bullets-in-beirut-protest.ashx|title=Security forces fire tear gas, rubber bullets in Beirut protest|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> At least 46 people were hospitalized with injuries according to the [[Lebanese Red Cross]] and [[Lebanese Civil Defense]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/15/middleeast/beirut-protest-intl/index.html|title=Violent protests erupt on streets of Beirut|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>{{tweet\n|text =        \u0648\u0644\u0645\u0627 \u062a\u0628\u064a\u0646 \u0644\u064a \u0627\u0646\u0647 \u0631\u063a\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0632\u0627\u0645\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u0637\u0639 \u0628\u062a\u0634\u0643\u064a\u0644 \u062d\u0643\u0648\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0635\u064a\u064a\u0646\u060c \u0641\u0625\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0627\u0642\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u064a \u0638\u0647\u0631\u062a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u064a\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0644\u064a\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0636\u064a\u0629 \u0645\u0646 \u0645\u0633\u0623\u0644\u0629 \u062a\u0633\u0645\u064a\u062a\u064a \u0647\u064a \u0645\u0648\u0627\u0642\u0641 \u063a\u064a\u0631 \u0642\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0629 \u0644\u0644\u062a\u0628\u062f\u064a\u0644\u060c \u0641\u0625\u0646\u0646\u064a \u0623\u0639\u0644\u0646 \u0627\u0646\u0646\u064a \u0644\u0646 \u0623\u0643\u0648\u0646 \u0645\u0631\u0634\u062d\u0627 \u0644\u062a\u0634\u0643\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0643\u0648\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0642\u0628\u0644\u0629\u060c \u0662/\u0663\n|name =        Saad Hariri\n|username =    saadhariri\n|date =        18 December 2019\n|ID =          1207325809754746881\n|lang =        ar\n|translation = And as it became clear to me that despite my categorical commitment to forming a government of specialists, the reactions of the past few days regarding my nomination were uncompromising, I announce that I will not be a candidate to form the next government, 2/3\n}}\n\nIn Beirut, protesters clashed with security forces on 15 December for the second night in a row near Nejmeh Square. According to the [[Lebanese Civil Defense]], 46 people were treated for injuries and another 14 were hospitalized.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50804392|title=Lebanon crisis: Dozens wounded in second night of clashes in Beirut|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> A group of counter-protesters, themselves supporters of [[Amal Movement|Amal]] and [[Hezbollah]], also briefly clashed with protesters until the army intervened.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/angry-confrontations-lebanon-parliament-sitting-191216030453163.html|title=Angry confrontations in Lebanon before parliament sitting|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\nRoads were blocked in [[North Governorate|northern Lebanon]] on 16 December. At noon, President Aoun delayed scheduled parliamentary consultations, where [[Saad Hariri]] was widely expected to be renamed Prime Minister. This was because Hariri was now no longer being supported by the main Christian parties in parliament.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-16/497515-day-61-roadblocks-in-north-quiet-in-beirut.ashx|title=Day 61: Roadblocks in North, Quiet in Beirut|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/lebanon-delays-nomination-pm-protests-divisions-191216162133861.html|title=Lebanon delays nomination of new PM amid protests, divisions|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> At night, protesters gathered close to Saad Hariri's Beirut residence to reject his reappointment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-17/497575-infiltrators-fail-to-intimidate-protesters.ashx|title=Infiltrators fail to intimidate protesters|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref> A separate group of protesters descended upon Beirut as well, expressing outrage at a month-old video of an expat insulting several [[Shi'a]] religious leaders. [[Amal Movement|Amal]] and [[Hezbollah]] released statements asking the men to fall back, but these calls were not immediately heeded.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.annahar.com/article/1087375-chaos-ensues-after-video-targetting-shiite-sect-goes-viral|title=Chaos ensues after video targeting Shiite figures goes viral|publisher=[[An-Nahar]]}}</ref> Protest encampments in several places, including Beirut, [[Saida, Lebanon|Saida]] and [[Nabatieh]], were ransacked and destroyed during the night. At least two cars in Beirut were set on fire.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-17/497595-protest-squares-attacked-in-beirut-south-lebanon-overnight.ashx|title=Protest squares attacked in Beirut, south Lebanon overnight|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/angry-shiites-clash-with-security-forces-in-beirut-opening-a-new-chapter-in-lebanons-crisis/2019/12/17/eb64ca8c-20b0-11ea-b034-de7dc2b5199b_story.html|title=Shiite groups' supporters clash with security forces in Beirut, opening a new chapter in Lebanon's crisis|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 December, Hariri announced that he did not want to be reappointed Prime Minister, calling on [[Michel Aoun|the president]] to designate a new Prime Minister immediately.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/lebanon-saad-hariri-pm-191126142134198.html|title=Lebanon's Saad Hariri says he does not want to be next PM|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> Later that day, [[Al Jadeed]] claimed that the remaining candidates for Prime Minister were now [[Tammam Salam]] (the 34th Prime Minister, 2014\u20132016), jurist [[Nawaf Salam]] (former representative of Lebanon to the [[United Nations]]), Khaled Mohieddin Qabbani (former Minister of Justice, 2005\u20132008) and academic [[Hassan Diab (minister)|Hassan Diab]] (former Minister of Education, 2011\u20132014).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.naharnet.com/stories/en/267371-hariri-withdraws-nomination-for-pm-post-urges-against-postponing-consultations|title=Hariri Withdraws Nomination for PM Post, Urges against Postponing Consultations|publisher=[[Naharnet]]}}</ref> Diab was the apparent favorite, because he had the support of [[Hezbollah]] and [[Amal Movement|Amal]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-18/497721-aub-professor-hassan-diab-emerges-as-favorite-for-pm-designation.ashx|title=AUB professor Hassan Diab emerges as favorite for PM designation|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://alkhaleejtoday.co/international/4970/Lebanons-Hariri-says-he-will-not-be-PM-again.html|title=Lebanon's Hariri says he will not be PM again|publisher=[[Al Khaleej (newspaper)|Al Khaleej Today]]}}</ref> Protests continued in [[Nabatieh]] and [[Kfar Remen]] despite threats of retaliation by Hezbollah and Amal supporters. Cement walls and blocs were erected around Beirut's central district, blocking off streets leading to and from [[Riad Al Solh Square]] as well a parliament.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/585248/World/Mena/Lebanon-ups-security-at-protest-sites-after-violence|title=Lebanon ups security at protest sites after violence|publisher=[[Saudi Gazette]]}}</ref>\n\nParliamentary consultations took place on 19 December and [[Hassan Diab (minister)|Hassan Diab]] was designated as the next Prime Minister to succeed Hariri.<ref name=\"auto\"/> The announcement of Diab becoming Prime Minister was immediately followed by street protests and road blocks in [[Tripoli]] and [[Beirut]]. Near Beirut's [[Beirut Central District|Nejme Square]], hundreds of protesters sang an anti-Diab chant.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/hezbollah-backed-hassan-diab-lebanon-pm-191219155153401.html|title=Lebanese president asks Hassan Diab to form government|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenth week: 20'''\u2013'''26 December ===\nRoad blocks in response to Diab's Prime Ministership continued across the country on 20 December. Schools were closed in Tripoli.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/roadblocks-lebanon-anger-rises-diab-pick-pm-191220091929392.html|title=Roadblocks across Lebanon as anger rises over Diab pick as PM|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 December, thousands protested against Diab's nomination on Beirut's [[Martyrs' Square, Beirut|Martyrs' Square]], many of them coming from the [[North Governorate|north]] of the [[Beqaa Valley]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191222-thousands-protest-in-lebanon-against-new-prime-minister-hassan-diab|title=Thousands protest in Lebanon against new Prime Minister Hassan Diab|publisher=[[France24]]}}</ref> Protests in Beirut continued on 23 December with a lower turnout.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/turnout-protesters-rally-lebanon-pm-191223071145129.html|title=Lower turnout as protesters rally against new Lebanon PM|publisher=[[Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> Later that day, hundreds of people shared a Christmas dinner benefiting the poor on Martyrs' Square.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Dec-23/497991-road-closures-in-north-on-day-68-of-protests.ashx|title=Hundreds share Christmas dinner in Martyrs' Square|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 December, it was reported that tourism fell by 80% because of the protest movements. Additionally, 265 restaurants and cafes closed their doors in the last two months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newspaper.annahar.com/article/1091656-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AD%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AC%D8%B9%D8%AA-80-%D9%88%D8%A5%D9%84%D8%BA%D8%A7%D8%A1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%AC%D9%88%D8%B2%D8%A7%D9%88%D8%B2%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B1-%D9%83%D9%8A%D8%AF%D8%A7%D9%86%D9%8A%D8%A7%D9%86-%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D9%85%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D8%AA%D8%AA%D8%B6%D9%85%D9%86|title=\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0627\u062d\u064a\u0629 \u062a\u0631\u0627\u062c\u0639\u062a 80% \u0648\u0625\u0644\u063a\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u062c\u0648\u0632\u0627\u062a \u0645\u0633\u062a\u0645\u0631... \u0643\u064a\u062f\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0627\u0646 \u0644\u0640\"\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0647\u0627\u0631\": \u0645\u0628\u0627\u062f\u0631\u0629 \u062a\u062a\u0636\u0645\u0651\u0646 \u0623\u0633\u0639\u0627\u0631\u0627\u064b \"\u0625\u063a\u0631\u0627\u0626\u064a\u0629\" \u0644\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0627\u062d|publisher=[[An-Nahar]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Eleventh week: 27'''\u2013'''31 December ===\nA group of pro-Hariri Sunni Muslims protested on 28 December 2019 in front of the new Prime Minister Diab calling for him to resign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/28/protesters-call-for-lebanons-new-pm-to-quit-as-crisis-deepens|title=Protesters call for Lebanon's new PM to quit as crisis deepens|publisher=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> On 29 December, protests continued asking for Hassan Diab's resignation although he is still continuing consultations to form the government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/mideast/2019/12/29/protesters-demand-new-pms-resignation-in-lebanon|title= Protesters demand new PM's resignation in Lebanon|publisher=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arabic.euronews.com/2019/12/29/lebanese-demonstrate-house-new-prime-minister-and-demand-resign|title=\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0648\u0646 \u064a\u062a\u0638\u0627\u0647\u0631\u0648\u0646 \u0623\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u0646\u0632\u0644 \u0631\u0626\u064a\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0643\u0648\u0645\u0629 \u062d\u0633\u0627\u0646 \u062f\u064a\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u062d\u062a\u062c\u0627\u062c\u0627 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u062a\u0643\u0644\u064a\u0641\u0647|publisher=[[Euronews]]}}</ref>\n\n== 2020 Protests ==\n=== Protests resume ===\nAfter weeks of relative calm, mass protests resumed across the country on 14 January 2020. Highways and major roads were blocked in [[Beirut]], [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]], [[Akkar District|Akkar]], [[Sidon]], and [[Zahl\u00e9|Zahle]] by protests and burning tires. In Beirut, protesters clashed with security forces outside the [[Banque du Liban|Central Bank]]. Protests also took place outside [[Hassan Diab (minister)|Hassan Diab's]] house for failing to form a government. President [[Michel Aoun]] blamed obstacles in the delay of formation of a new government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2081976/lebanese-protesters-clash-police-outside-central-bank-aoun-blames-%E2%80%98obstacles%E2%80%99|title=Lebanese Protesters Clash with Police outside Central Bank as Aoun Blames 'Obstacles' for Govt. Delay|last=|first=|date=14 January 2020|work=Asharq Al-Awsat|access-date=14 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/protesters-block-roads-lebanon-anti-gov-rallies-resume-200114113206147.html|title=Protesters block roads in Lebanon as anti-gov't rallies resume|last=|first=|date=14 January 2020|work=aljazeera.com|access-date=14 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Times of Israel added that school and university students participated in some of the demonstrations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/lebanese-protesters-back-in-streets-following-brief-lull/|title=Lebanese protesters back in streets following brief lull|last=Deeb|first=Sarah El|date=14 January 2020|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 15 January, protesters gathered in front of the Helou police barracks in Beirut demanding the release of more than 50 protesters who were arrested the night before. During the protest, riot police fired tear gas and practiced excessive violence to separate protesters. Additionally, an estimated number of 15 protesters were dragged into the barracks. The Lebanese Media reported that there have been more than 30 injuries as a result of the clashes that happened between the protesters and the riot police. The Lebanese Army also arrived at the scene later on that night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2020/Jan-16/499322-protesters-close-roads-call-for-release-of-detainees.ashx|title=Protesters close roads, call for release of detainees|date=16 January 2020|website=The Daily Star|url-status=live|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2020/Jan-15/499320-violence-arrests-outside-helou-barracks.ashx|title=Violence, arrests outside Helou barracks|date=15 January 2020|website=The Daily Star|url-status=live|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref> It was reported by the Red Cross that the wounded people on Wednesday had reached 45, according to ''DW''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/un-envoy-slams-lebanons-leaders-as-protests-rock-beirut/a-52019256|title=UN envoy slams Lebanon's leaders as protests rock Beirut|date=16 January 2020|website=DW|language=en-GB|url-status=live|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> According to Reuters, Lebanon\u2019s Minister of Interior has issued a statement criticizing the violence and urging the protesters to remain peaceful.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-protests-idUSKBN1ZE2WP|title=Lebanon protests turn violent for second night|date=15 January 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=21 January 2020|language=en}}</ref> \n\nAs the Lebanese protests enter its fourth month on 17 January, protesters blocked several main roads across Lebanon, including a vital road connecting central Beirut\u2019s east and west. Hundreds of protesters were said to have also gathered outside the Lebanese central bank and close to the parliament, the Times of Israel added.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/lebanese-demonstrators-block-roads-as-protests-enter-fourth-month/|title=Lebanese demonstrators block roads as protests enter fourth month|last=AFP|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> On Friday morning, the roads were also blocked in second city Tripoli by protesters, but later in the day the roads were cleared, according to France 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200118-lebanon-protest-fourth-month-political-elite|title=Lebanese block roads as revived protests enter fourth month|date=18 January 2020|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> Human Rights Watch has urged authorities to free detainees that haven\u2019t been charged with a recognizable crime and that the Ministry of Interior should quickly hold security officers responsible for the excessive use of force on protesters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/01/17/lebanon-police-violence-against-protesters|title=Lebanon: Police Violence Against Protesters|date=17 January 2020|website=Human Rights Watch|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> HRW also claimed that protesters and media officials had been struck by riot police, according to Al Jazeera.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/lebanon-releases-protesters-rights-groups-slam-security-forces-200117082501361.html|title=Lebanon releases protesters as rights groups slam security forces|date=17 January 2020|website=www.aljazeera.com|url-status=live|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Escalation of violence and arrest of journalist ===\nIn an attempt to break up gatherings of anti-government protesters attempting to reach Martyr\u2019s Square on 18 January, dozens of people have been injured as security forces used water cannons and tear gas to dissipate the protesters. Furthermore, demonstrators have been spotted at Martyr\u2019s Square throwing rocks, fireworks and Molotov cocktails at security forces, as well as shining lasers at them to interrupt series of tear gas rounds, CNN reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/lebanon-anti-government-protests-turn-violent-beirut-200118160101017.html|title=Scores wounded as Lebanon's anti-gov't protests turn violent|date=19 January 2020|website=www.aljazeera.com|url-status=live|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/18/middleeast/beirut-protests-lebanon-intl/index.html|title=Lebanon police fire tear gas at protesters in violent 'week of rage'|last=Wedeman|first=Ben|last2=Balkiz|first2=Ghazi|date=18 January 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|access-date=21 January 2020|last3=Streib|first3=Christian|last4=Dewan|first4=Angela}}</ref> In the evening, President Aoun summoned in the armed forces to the streets in order to safeguard private property, as well as peaceful protesters, the ABC News reported.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/protests-lebanon-reach-intensity-dozens-hospital-analysis/story?id=68404196|title=Protests in Lebanon reach new intensity, dozens taken to hospital: Analysis|last=McGarry|first=Matt|date=20 January 2020|website=ABC News|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref> About 30 people were said to have been detained due to Saturday\u2019s unrest, the state-run National News Agency stated, though the detainees were later released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/world/world/2020/01/557904/400-hurt-lebanon-protesters-clash-security-forces|title=400 hurt as Lebanon protesters clash with security forces|last=AFP|date=19 January 2020|website=New Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref> More than 60 wounded people are believed to have received treatment, while at least 40 people have been rushed to the hospitals, the Lebanese Red Cross stated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6430731/lebanon-protests-beirut-government/|title=Lebanon anti-government protests near parliament building leave dozens wounded|last=Reuters|date=18 January 2020|website=Global News|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> In total, Reuters reported that more than 370 people had been injured in the day's protests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-crisis-protests-idUSKBN1ZI0DS|title=Lebanese security forces, protesters clash for second night|last=Francis|first=Ellen|date=19 January 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=20 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Nader|first2=Yara Abi|editor-last=Perry|editor-first=Tom|language=en|last3=Perry|first3=Tom|last4=Kanaan|first4=Alaa|editor-last2=Graff|editor-first2=Peter|editor-last3=Russell|editor-first3=Ros|editor-last4=Macfie|editor-first4=Nick}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 January, an American freelance journalist Nicholas Frakes was arrested on the allegation of sending footage of anti-government protests to the Israeli newspaper Haaretz, according to the Washington Post.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-journalist-detained-during-lebanon-protests-on-suspicion-of-sending-footage-to-israel/2020/01/20/33b9947a-3bb4-11ea-afe2-090eb37b60b1_story.html|title=U.S. journalist detained during Lebanon protests on suspicion of sending footage to Israel|last=Sly|first=Liz|date=20 January 2020|work=The Washington Post|access-date=21 January 2020|url-status=live|last2=Haidamous|first2=Suzan}}</ref> However, Haaretz Newspaper has rejected any connection to Nicholas Frakes, arguing that the live video feed of the anti-government protest uploaded on their Facebook account was from Reuters, the Jerusalem Post added.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Middle-East/Haaretz-denies-any-connection-to-journalist-arrested-in-Lebanon-614757|title=Haaretz denies any connection to journalist arrested in Lebanon|last=Joffre|first=Tzvi|date=21 January 2020|website=The Jerusalem Post|url-status=live|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> The Committee to Protect Journalists (CPJ) claimed that since 14 January, journalists reporting anti-government protests in Beirut have been arrested, attacked or molested by police officers, according to the International Business Times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.sg/american-journalist-arrested-by-lebanese-military-over-reporting-israeli-enemy-newspaper-38024|title=American journalist arrested by Lebanese military over reporting for 'Israeli enemy newspaper'|date=21 January 2020|website=International Business Times, Singapore Edition|language=en|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> According to France 24, In light of this week\u2019s World Economic Forum, the expected participation of Lebanon\u2019s outgoing foreign minister Gebran Bassil has triggered a strong public protest, demanding the cancellation of his invitation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200120-public-uproar-in-protest-hit-lebanon-over-fm-s-davos-invite|title=Public uproar in protest-hit Lebanon over FM's Davos invite|date=20 January 2020|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref> However, Bassil maintains that the protesters who chanted against him do not make up the majority of Lebanese and that he believes the people of Lebanon want change, but he argued that he\u2019s not leaving until voters drive him out in elections, according to the Washington Post. The former foreign minister further claimed that he came to Davos \u201con his own expenses\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/01/23/world/middleeast/ap-ml-davos-lebanon.html|title=Lawmaker Targeted by Lebanese Protests Rejects Calls to Quit|date=23 January 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=24 January 2020|url-status=live|agency=The Associated Press|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/23/lebanons-former-foreign-minister-tries-to-defend-davos-trip.html|title=Lebanon's former foreign minister tries to defend Davos trip as country faces economic collapse|last=Turak|first=Natasha|date=23 January 2020|website=CNBC|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref> As of 21 January, there has been an increase in the number of injured people in the Lebanese protests to more 540, according to ''The Times of Israel''.<ref name=\"540injured\" >{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/lebanon-officials-vow-to-deter-infiltrator-attacks-after-weekend-violence/|title=Lebanon officials vow to deter 'infiltrator' attacks after weekend violence|last=Osseiran|first=Hashem|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== New government formed === \nOn 21 January, Prime Minister Diab announced the formation of a new cabinet of 20 ministers, bringing an end to several months of impasse that has left the country in a deepening economic crisis. According to CNN, during an interview with Lebanon\u2019s state news agency, Diab portrayed the newly appointed ministers as \"technocrats\" who he believes would operate without loyalties to political parties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51189782|title=New Lebanon government ends months of deadlock|date=22 January 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=22 January 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/21/world/lebanon-prime-minister-govt-intl/index.html|title=After months of protest, Lebanon forms new government|last=Balkiz|first=Ghazi|last2=Alkhshali|first2=Hamdi|date=21 January 2020|website=CNN|url-status=live|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref> Even before the new cabinet was unveiled, several groups of protesters had gathered in the streets of Beirut, obstructing a main street in the center of the capital, according to France 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200121-lebanon-beirut-hassan-diab-saad-hariri-new-government-protests-cabinet|title=Lebanon announces new government, protestors far from impressed|date=21 January 2020|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref> The Times of Israel added that the protesters made an effort to take down barbed wire near the parliament building and throw rocks at security forces, who in return used tear gas and water cannons. Some protesters maintained that they would remain in the streets, till their claims for a technocratic government and early elections were met, according to Al Jazeera.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/protests-in-lebanon-continue-as-new-government-fails-to-assuage-anger/|title=Protests in Lebanon continue as new government fails to assuage anger|last=AFP|date=22 January 2020|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/lebanon-announces-formation-government-200121200947113.html|title=Lebanon announces formation of new government|date=22 January 2020|website=www.aljazeera.com|url-status=live|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to VOA, despite the fact that the newly formed ministers are experts and academics, protesters are still accusing political groups of participating in forming the new cabinet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/new-government-crisis-hit-lebanon-protests-continue|title=New Government in Crisis-Hit Lebanon, But Protests Continue|date=22 January 2020|website=Voice of America|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref> On 22 January, as Lebanon\u2019s new government convened, protesters in the capital gathered to discredit the meeting, smashing windows and breaking down security blockages encircling the parliament building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/violent-protests-beirut-follow-lebanon-cabinet-meeting-200122161944258.html|title='They're still robbing us': Angry Lebanese reject new government|date=22 January 2020|website=www.aljazeera.com|url-status=live|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAmnesty International, based on evidence collected, has accused the Internal Security Forces of using rubber bullets unlawfully at close range, besides beatings, water cannons and tear gas in an attempt to disperse protesters on the weekend, which has left hundreds wounded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2020/01/lebanon-new-government-must-immediately-rein-in-security-forces-after-weekend-of-violence/|title=Lebanon: New government must immediately rein in security forces after weekend of violence|date=23 January 2020|website=www.amnesty.org|publisher=[[Amnesty International]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref> 25 January marked the 100th day since the protests began.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/01/25/lebanon-protests-torture/|title=As the Lebanon Uprising Hits 100-Day Mark, Protesters Allege Torture by Security Forces|last=Medina|first=Daniel A.|last2=Chehayeb|first2=Kareem|date=25 January 2020|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Protesters gathered in Beirut and breached several security barriers around the central government building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200125-lebanese-protesters-rally-in-beirut-to-mark-100-days-of-demonstrations|title=Lebanese protesters rally in Beirut to mark 100 days of demonstrations|date=25 January 2020|work=France 24|access-date=28 January 2020|url-status=live|agency=AFP|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 January, the [[Parliament of Lebanon|Lebanon Parliament]] passed a 2020 budget, amid the debilitating financial crisis. The state budget came as the protests outside the Parliament in [[Beirut]] were held back by the [[Internal Security Forces|security forces]].<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com/news/nation-world/world/article239672548.html|title= Heavy security in Beirut as parliament convenes on budget |access-date=27 January 2020|website=The Herald Sun}}</ref> Four people had been injured and taken to the hospitals in Beirut, with 8 other people sustaining minor injuries, the Lebanese Red Cross announced.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.arabnews.com/node/1618831/middle-east |title= Lebanese parliament approves 2020 budget|access-date=31 January 2020|date= 27 January 2020}}</ref> The state-run National News Agency stated that only 70 out of the 128 members of parliament attended Monday\u2019s vote, with 49 lawmakers in favor of passing the budget, 13 against and 8 forgoing.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.france24.com/en/20200127-lebanon-parliament-passes-2020-budget-amid-protests |title= Lebanon parliament passes 2020 budget amid protests. |date= 27 January 2020 }}</ref> According to Al Jazeera, analysts argue that the endorsed 2020 budget barely attempts to resolve Lebanon\u2019s financial and economic crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/ajimpact/lebanon-passes-budget-critics-call-useless-piece-paper-200127190315527.html |title= Lebanon passes budget critics call 'useless piece of paper'|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to SBS News, the parliament budget committee chairman Ibrahim Kanaan stated that the purpose of the new budget is to lower deficit of gross domestic product to around 7%.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.sbs.com.au/news/lebanon-passes-new-budget-amid-anti-government-protests |title= Lebanon passes new budget amid anti-government protests.|website=SBS.com.au|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref> Experts have warned that the direction in which Lebanon is heading could ignite more instability, as the newly formed government is not expected to convince Lebanese protesters to end their demonstrations against the ruling elite, according to VOA.<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.voanews.com/extremism-watch/experts-new-hezbollah-backed-cabinet-unlikely-calm-protests-lebanon |title= Experts: New Hezbollah-backed Cabinet Unlikely to Calm Protests in Lebanon|date=30 January 2020|last=Ahmado|first=Nisan|work=Voice of America|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 February, a protest was held outside the United States embassy in Beirut, by hundreds of Lebanese and Palestinians, in opposition to the US plan for ending the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/protesters-outside-us-embassy-in-lebanon-decry-trump-plan/ |title= Protesters outside US Embassy in Lebanon decry Trump plan. |}}</ref> Protesters were gathered on a road leading to the US embassy, northeast of Beirut, waving Palestinian flags, with some of the protesters chanting \u201cDeath to America! Death to Israel! We will die and Palestine survive,\" according to France 24. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.france24.com/en/20200202-lebanon-us-palestine-palestinian-israel-peace-plan-protest-beirut-embassy-abbas-trump-white-house-mahmoud-arab-league-refugee-middle-east |title= Hundreds protest against US Mideast peace plan in Lebanon. |}}</ref> It was reported by the VOA News that around noon, security forces used what seemed to be pepper spray to stop some of the protesters who had removed the barbed wire and reached a metal fence set up by security forces. At least three protesters were said to have been carried away in the process of the struggle. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/protesters-outside-us-embassy-lebanon-decry-trump-plan |title= Protesters Outside US Embassy in Lebanon Decry Trump Plan. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/lebanese-protesters-decry-trump-plan-outside-u-s-embassy-1.8478014 |title= Lebanese Protesters Decry Trump Plan Outside U.S. Embassy. |}}</ref> According to Arab News, 24 hours prior to the protest, employees of the US embassy were advised to stay clear of the area of the protests. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.arabnews.com/node/1621966/middle-east |title= Lebanese security forces pepper spray demonstrators outside US Embassy. |}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in an attempt to prove to the government that the Lebanese people are united in their quest for political change, protesters were also reported to have gathered in Tripoli, the country\u2019s poorest city on Sunday, according to Al Jazeera. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/lebanon-protesters-gather-tripoli-poverty-corruption-200202121944585.html |title= Lebanon: Protesters gather in Tripoli against poverty, corruption. |}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Middle East Monitor, In a statement issued by the Lebanese Information Minister Abdul Samad 6 February, he disclosed that the new government of Lebanon has agreed to the approval of a new policy statement, which is believed to include a clause calling for the return of refugees back to their various countries. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200206-lebanon-president-to-force-displaced-persons-to-return-home/ |title= Lebanon president to force displaced persons to return home. |}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February, women\u2019s groups at the local level in Lebanon, including other alienated groups, are demanding for their rights to be honored by the Lebanese government, Al Jazeera reported. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/women-call-rights-lead-change-lebanon-protests-200210083905972.html |title= Women call for rights, lead change in Lebanon protests. |}}</ref>\n\nOn Tuesday, the Lebanese parliament held a nine-hour session, in which the legislators passed a vote of confidence, supporting the newly formed cabinet by the Lebanese government, and its financial rescue plan. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/lebanon-gov-wins-parliament-confidence-vote-protests-200211151210371.html |title= Lebanon gov't wins Parliament's confidence vote despite protests. |}}</ref> Protesters attempted to disrupt the meeting from holding by throwing stones at security forces, and tried to block the path leading to the parliament. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.euronews.com/2020/02/11/watch-live-protests-in-lebanon-ahead-of-government-confidence-vote |title= Lebanon government wins confidence vote as protests rage in Beirut. |}}</ref> The parliament meeting was attended by 84 members of parliament, with 63 of them voting in support of the government, France 24 added. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.france24.com/en/20200211-protesters-clash-with-security-forces-in-lebanon-ahead-of-cabinet-vote-of-confidence |title= Lebanese govt wins no confidence vote despite protests. |}}</ref> In an attempt by protesters to evade security checkpoints, they started to form up at various points in Beirut, but some lawmakers reportedly spent the night in the parliament ahead of the meeting, in order to avoid being prevented by protesters. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.timesofisrael.com/security-forces-use-tear-gas-as-lebanon-protesters-try-to-block-confidence-vote/ |title= Security forces use tear gas as Lebanon protesters try to block confidence vote. |}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, Former Prime Minister Saad Hariri delivered his first speech after leaving office in October, urging that he is not leaving Lebanon, but mapping out a new future in politics with his party. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/defiant-lebanon-hariri-deal-aoun-history-200214172027571.html |title= Defiant, Lebanon's Hariri says deal with Aoun is 'history'. |}}</ref> In response to Lebanon\u2019s request for technical assistance from the IMF earlier in February, hundreds of protesters have gathered around Lebanon\u2019s central bank and parliament on 15 February, in rejection of the request. <ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-02/15/c_138787196.htm |title= Hundreds of Lebanese protest against gov't request for IMF support. |}}</ref>\n\nThe World Bank has warned Lebanon against the risk of implosion, if they fail to adopt a new system of governance that is more genuine and transparent compared to the old one. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-17/lebanon-warned-of-implosion-as-imf-world-bank-plead-for-reforms |title= Lebanon Warned of Implosion as IMF, World Bank Plead for Reforms. |}}</ref> Lebanon\u2019s Prime Minister Hassan Diab hosted the speaker of the Iranian Parliament Ali Larijani on 17 February, as Iran expresses readiness to assist Lebanon with its ongoing crisis. The Iranian speaker added that, considering Lebanon has made it all the way past the creation of a new government, Iran is now ready to assume their responsibility, which involves working with Lebanon, according to the Tasnim News Agency. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/voa-news-iran/snubbed-gulf-lebanons-pm-diab-hosts-iranian-official |title= Snubbed by Gulf, Lebanon's PM Diab Hosts Iranian Official. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.tasnimnews.com/en/news/2020/02/18/2205361/iran-ready-to-cooperate-with-lebanon-s-new-gov-t-in-all-areas-speaker |title= Iran Ready to Cooperate with Lebanon\u2019s New Gov\u2019t in All Areas: Speaker. |}}</ref> According to The New York Times, several Lebanese are considering emigration as a solution to the ongoing deepening crisis in Lebanon which has no end date, with some in possession of a second passport already, which will pave way for them to leave the country without any difficulty.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/02/19/world/middleeast/19reuters-lebanon-crisis-emigration.html |title= Crisis Drives Lebanese Abroad in Search of Better Future. |}}</ref>\n\nDuring the G-20 Summit in Riyadh On 23 February, Saudi Arabia\u2019s finance minister divulged Saudi\u2019s plan of assisting Lebanon with its financial crisis, once there is assurance that Lebanon has put in place a solid reform plan. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/23/saudi-arabia-will-support-lebanon-if-it-sees-viable-reform-plan.html |title= Saudi Arabia is ready to support debt-ridden Lebanon \u2014 but wants to see a reform plan first, finance minister says. |}}</ref> Also during the summit, the finance minister of France has expressed his country's willingness to provide Lebanon with any form of financial support if need be. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/02/23/business/23reuters-g20-saudi-france-lebanon-exclusive.html |title= Exclusive: If Lebanon Needs Financial Aid, France Will Be There, Finmin Says. |}}</ref> Furthermore, the Lebanese government is trying to set up an emergency economic plan that will improve the country\u2019s conditions, amid fears of acquiring aid from the international community. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/lebanon-economy-govt-works-emergency-financial-plan-200227120107841.html |title= Lebanon economy: Gov't works towards emergency financial plan. |}}</ref> Several migrant workers in Lebanon are paying the price for the country\u2019s financial crisis, as the access to hard currency has been limited, France 24 reported. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.france24.com/en/20200227-in-lebanon-migrant-workers-hit-by-financial-crisis |title= In Lebanon, migrant workers hit by financial crisis. |}}</ref>\n\nDue to religious restrictions guarding the country\u2019s system of protection, Lebanon\u2019s Prime Minister Hassan Diab stated on 2 March, that the government has become unable to protect the Lebanese citizens. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200303-lebanon-pm-we-can-no-longer-protect-our-people/ |title= Lebanon PM: 'We can no longer protect our people'. |}}</ref> Lebanon\u2019s huge debts have caste doubts on the ability of Lebanon to meet repayment due by 9 March, as several members of parliament reject paying the $1.2bn Euro-bond, regardless of the consequences, the speaker of parliament disclosed on 4 March. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/ajimpact/lebanese-mps-oppose-paying-debt-means-default-200304213537786.html |title= Most Lebanese MPs oppose paying debt even if it means default. |}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March, Lebanese came out in hundreds near banks in Southern Lebanon, to protest against the regulations stopping them from withdrawing their funds. <ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/05/c_138846804.htm |title= Hundreds protest against banks, money exchange companies in southern Lebanon. |}}</ref> However, the Lebanese parliament is believed to have passed a bill to ensure that banking secrecy has been lifted, the Minister of Justice in Lebanon, Marie-Claude Najm stated. Lebanon\u2019s minister of information also added that, the law is expected to be applicable to members of parliament, ministers, as well as public officials. <ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/05/c_138847039.htm |title= Lebanon passes law to lift banking secrecy. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-crisis-banks/lebanons-financial-prosecutor-freezes-assets-of-20-banks-idUSKBN20S2HR |title= Lebanon state prosecutor blocks order to freeze assets of 20 banks. |}}</ref> As the exchange rate of US dollar-Lebanese pound reaches LL2,600 on Thursday, hundreds of demonstrators took to the streets in Antelias and Beirut, demanding for the government to find a solution, as well as to hold early elections. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2020/Mar-05/502278-hundreds-of-protesters-call-for-early-elections.ashx |title= Protests renewed as exchange rate hits LL2,600. |}}</ref> Considering the current economic situation in Lebanon, a judge has reportedly halted an order of assets freezing of 20 banks, including their directors. The judge explained the reason for suspending the order, stating that he wants to first learn how the order could affect Lebanon\u2019s current economic position. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.egypttoday.com/Article/2/82358/Lebanon-suspends-asset-freeze-on-20-banks |title= Lebanon suspends asset freeze on 20 banks. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/ajimpact/lebanon-prosecutor-orders-assets-frozen-20-local-banks-200305165951273.html |title= Lebanese judge suspends prosecutor\u2019s order to freeze bank assets. |}}</ref>\n\nOn March 7, Prime minister Hassan Diab said that Lebanon would [[Default (finance)|default]] on a Eurobond repayment and pursue restructuring its debt. The country has never before defaulted. Lebanon's government debt is about 170% of its yearly gross domestic product. Several Analysts have added that only the IMF\u2019s support could be the solution to Lebanon\u2019s financial crisis after the default.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/07/lebanon-to-default-on-debt-for-first-time-amid-financial-crisis|title=Lebanon to default on debt for first time amid financial crisis|website=The Guardian|date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.vaticannews.va/en/world/news/2020-03/lebanon-debt-crisis-protests-default.html |title= Lebanon defaults on sovereign debt after months of protests. |}}</ref> However, hundreds of protesters have reportedly continued their rally which commenced earlier on Thursday, in several cities across the country including Sidon, as they criticise against the financial policies and poor standard of living in the country. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2020/Mar-07/502353-protests-march-on-banks-in-beirut-and-sidon.ashx |title= Protests march on across Lebanon against economic situation. |}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, Prime Minister Hassan Diab announced that Lebanon had defaulted on a $1.2 billion Eurobond, for the very first time in the history of the country. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2020/03/12/leba-m12.html |title= Amid protests and crises, Lebanon defaults on Eurobond. |}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the restriction on deposits due to shortage of foreign currency was reduced by a public prosecutor, as he consented with rules for commercial banks, targeted at defending depositors rights. The decision was verified by an official at the office of the public prosecutor, even though no additional comment was given. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://aawsat.com/english/home/article/2173291/lebanon-banks-prosecutor-agree-rules-easing-deposit-restrictions |title= Lebanon Banks, Prosecutor Agree Rules for Easing Deposit Restrictions. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-crisis-banks/lebanon-banks-prosecutor-agree-rules-for-easing-deposit-restrictions-idUSKBN20X2QW |title= Lebanon banks, prosecutor agree rules for easing deposit restrictions. |}}</ref>\n\nAmid fears of the further spread of coronavirus in Lebanon, on 15 March, the government decided to put in place a state of emergency, leaving its crippling economy in a stalemate. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.thetrumpet.com/22119-coronavirus-hastens-lebanons-impending-economic-collapse |title= Coronavirus Hastens Lebanon\u2019s Impending Economic Collapse. |}}</ref> The decision was reached after several hours of an emergency cabinet meeting which resulted to the closure of its land borders, seaports and the Rafic Hariri International Airport in Beirut. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/lebanon-shut-airport-restrict-movement-coronavirus-200316101635705.html |title= Lebanon will shut airport, restrict movement over coronavirus. |}}</ref> According to Reuters, the closure which commenced on Wednesday, is expected to be in place until 29th of March, so as to enable the state of health emergency that has been set up, to tackle the virus effectively. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-lebanon-pm/lebanon-to-shut-airport-from-wednesday-in-coronavirus-measure-idUSS8N27C01R |title= Lebanon to shut airport from Wednesday in coronavirus measure. |}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, the Lebanese government decided to stop paying back all debts in foreign currencies, in light of the fall in foreign currency reserves and worsening financial and economic crisis. Coronavirus pandemic has caused many businesses to be closed down, including a severe impact on the foreign sector, which influenced the government\u2019s new decision. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/lebanon-to-stop-paying-back-all-debt-in-foreign-currencies/2020/03/23/1036cb18-6d04-11ea-a156-0048b62cdb51_story.html |title= Lebanon to stop paying back all debt in foreign currencies. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.arabnews.com/node/1645951/business-economy |title= Lebanon to stop paying back all debt in foreign currencies. |}}</ref> The Lebanese finance ministry added that the country is planning on reaching reasonable understanding with its creditors immediately. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.nation.co.ke/business/Lebanon-to-stop-paying-outstanding-Eurobonds/996-5501752-ogot4qz/index.html |title= Lebanon to stop paying outstanding Eurobonds: ministry. |}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, camps in Martyrs Square in central Beirut, which has been mostly occupied by protesters since October 2019, were reportedly cleared by Lebanon\u2019s security forces, according to the National Post. The security forces engaged the Martyrs Square in the evening after the Lebanese cabinet had imposed a curfew. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/lebanese-police-remove-beirut-protest-camp |title= Lebanese police remove Beirut protest camp. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2020/Mar-27/503456-protesters-cry-foul-play-as-police-destroy-encampments-in-downtown-beirut.ashx |title= Protesters cry foul play as police destroy encampments in downtown Beirut. |}}</ref> The decision to remove the camps was made amid growing concerns over the further spread of coronavirus, according to the Lebanese government. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/lebanon-decision-to-dismantle-protest-camps-over-coronavirus-fears-causes-controversy-1.999165 |title= Lebanon: decision to dismantle protest camps over coronavirus fears causes controversy. |}}</ref> However, protesters claimed that the police neither informed or gave them a notice, instead, they instructed them to quickly vacate the protest site. A protester added that there were only about 50 to 60 of them remaining when the security forces invaded the camps, as most of the protesters had evacuated the camps following the closure of seaports and airport of Beirut by the Lebanese government on 18 March, according to the Al-Monitor. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.arabnews.com/node/1648766/middle-east |title= Lebanon\u2019s police clear protest camps in Beirut as coronavirus curfew takes effect. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2020/03/lebanon-protests-coronavirus-support-poor-economy.html |title= Coronavirus forces Lebanese protesters into new posture. |}}</ref> Activists and journalists in Lebanon have expressed their concerns on the suspicion that the Lebanese government might be using the coronavirus outbreak as an excuse to make its powers even stronger. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.voanews.com/extremism-watch/lebanese-activists-fear-hezbollah-led-government-using-coronavirus-solidify-power |title= Lebanese Activists Fear Hezbollah-led Government Is Using Coronavirus to Solidify Power. |}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, some activists and journalists defied the lock down that was issued by the cabinet on 15 March to prevent the widespread of COVID-19, protesting against the closure of banks which led to the arrest of six activists and a journalist by the Lebanese security forces. The small group of protesters gathered in front of the Al-Mawarid Bank\u2019s Hamra branch in west Beirut, with some people putting on surgical masks and others without, Al-Arabiya added. <ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2020/Apr-02/503727-activists-detained-after-bank-protest.ashx |title= Activists detained after bank protest. |}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2020/Apr-02/503727-activists-detained-after-bank-protest.ashx |title= Activists, journalist arrested in Lebanon after defying coronavirus lockdown. |}}</ref>\n\n== Killing of Alaa Abou Fakhr ==\nOn the evening of 12 November, Alaa Abou Fakhr,<ref name=\"An-Nahar\" /> a Lebanese national, was shot and killed in [[Khalde]] at the ensuing protests. Abou Fakhr's death appeared to have been unprovoked, as he was unarmed and attending the protest with his wife and child. The Lebanese Army released a statement saying that his death occurred as an accident after a soldier fired shots purely with the intent to clear a path for an army convoy, and that the soldier had been referred to military court for a trial.<ref>{{cite news|title=Man killed as protests sweep Lebanon after Aoun interview|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-protests/man-killed-as-protests-sweep-lebanon-after-aoun-interview-idUSKBN1XM1DH|access-date=12 November 2019|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=lebarmyofficial|number=1194382014633431043 |date=12 November 2019|title=#\u0627\u0644\u062c\u064a\u0634_\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0628\u0646\u0627\u0646\u064a #Lebanesearmy}}</ref> However, during Abou Fakhr's funeral ceremony the next day, his wife, who was present with Abou Fakhr during his shooting, claimed that he was killed by Lebanese military intelligence.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=chehayebk|date=12 November 2019|number=1194572827489423360|title=@ALJADEEDNEWS briefly showed the funeral/reception held by Alaa Abou Fakhr. His wife repeatedly said \u201cMilitary intelligence killed him\u201d}}</ref> Abou Fakhr's death was the first to be caused by the Lebanese army.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lebanese man shot by army in first such death as tensions spike after president tells protesters to emigrate|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/11/13/lebanese-man-shot-army-first-death-tensions-spike-president/|access-date=13 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]}}</ref> A video circulating on social media appeared to show a plainclothes man who drove a civilian automobile shooting Abou Fakhr at close range.<ref>{{Cite news|title=L'homme bless\u00e9 \u00e0 Khald\u00e9 est d\u00e9c\u00e9d\u00e9|url=https://libnanews.com/lhomme-blesse-a-khalde-est-decede/|access-date=13 November 2019|publisher=Libnanews}}</ref>\n\nAbou Fakhr was a member of the Municipal Committee of [[Choueifat]] as a representative of the Lebanese [[Progressive Socialist Party]]. [[Walid Jumblatt]], the party's leader, appeared among protesters to call for calm after mounting animosity towards the Lebanese army, urging that \"the state is our only refuge or else we will descend into chaos\".<ref>{{cite AV media|date=12 November 2019|title=\u062c\u0646\u0628\u0644\u0627\u0637 \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u062a\u0634\u0641\u0649 \u0644\u0645\u0646\u0627\u0635\u0631\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0634\u062a\u0631\u0627\u0643\u064a \u062d\u0637\u0651\u0648\u0647\u0627 \u0641\u064a\u064a \u0648\u0645\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0627 \u0645\u0644\u062c\u0623 \u0627\u0644\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u060c \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0651 \u0646\u0630\u0647\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0648\u0636|trans-title=Jumblatt Speaks to Supporters in Front of Hospital: \"Believe me when I say we have no refuge other than the state, or else we will descend into chaos\"|location=Lebanon|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kLkJ2C3YVvI|publisher=[[Al Jadeed]]}}</ref> Abou Fakhr's death triggered a substantial increase in protest activity, with reported clashes with army forces and additional roads being barricaded in protest. Tributes and candlelight vigils were held for Abou Fakhr across Lebanon and were attended by thousands of protesters, who came to perceive him as symbolizing a martyr for the revolutionary movement. Abou Fakhr's family received condolences from virtually every Lebanese political faction.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Liban : la mort d'Alaa Abou Fakhr, tu\u00e9 par un militaire, rend la situation dramatique et explosive|url=https://eteignezvotreordinateur.com/liban-la-mort-dalaa-abou-fakhr-tue-par-un-militaire-rend-la-situation-dramatique-et-explosive/|access-date=13 November 2019|publisher=Eteignez Votre Ordinateur}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 November, the Lebanese Army announced that the suspected killer, First Adjutant Charbel Hjeil, had been referred to the military judiciary to await trial after the conclusion of the army's interrogation process.<ref>{{Cite tweet|title=\u0625\u0644\u062d\u0627\u0642\u0627\u064b \u0628\u0628\u064a\u0627\u0646\u0647\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0628\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u0639\u0644\u0642 \u0628\u062d\u0627\u062f\u062b\u0629 \u0625\u0637\u0644\u0627\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u0645\u0646\u0637\u0642\u0629 \u062e\u0644\u062f\u0629\u060c \u0623\u062d\u0627\u0644\u062a \u0645\u062f\u064a\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062e\u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u0627\u0648\u0646 \u0623\u0648\u0644 \u0634\u0631\u0628\u0644 \u0639\u062c\u064a\u0644 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0636\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0651\u060c \u0648\u0630\u0644\u0643 \u0628\u0639\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u062a\u0647\u0627\u0621 \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062d\u0642\u064a\u0642 \u0645\u0639\u0647 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0627\u062f\u062b\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u064a \u0623\u062f\u0651\u062a \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0634\u0647\u0627\u062f \u0639\u0644\u0627\u0621 \u0623\u0628\u0648 \u0641\u062e\u0631.|number=1194685385282113536|date=13 November 2019|user=lebarmyofficial}}</ref> A massive funeral procession was held in the evening with tens of thousands of attendees, with Abou Fakhr's coffin carried throughout Beirut.<ref>{{Cite news|title=A National Mourning Across Lebanon for the Revolution Martyr Alaa Abou Fakher|url=https://www.the961.com/news/a-national-mourning-across-lebanon-for-the-revolution-martyr-alaa-abou-fakher|date=14 November 2019|access-date=22 November 2019|publisher=The961}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 November, the Lebanese Army announced that First Adjutant Charbel Hjeil was charged with the murder of Alaa Abou Fakhr. The Colonel on the scene, Nidal Daou, also received unspecified charges. Sources claimed that Daou and Abou Fakhr were acquainted prior to the murder, implying a personal motive. The investigation was then slated to continue on 25 November.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=chehayebk|number=1197497715015507970|date=21 November 2019|title=#Lebanon Military Prosecutor charges the soldier who killed protestor Alaa Abu Fakhr w/murder, shooting warning rounds into the air, & threatening protestors at the Khalde roadblock. The colonel who was w/him was also charged. Investigation continues next Monday}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Military Prosecutor charges colonel at scene of Abou Fakher killing|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2019/Nov-21/496039-military-prosecutor-charges-colonel-at-scene-of-abou-fakher-killing.ashx|access-date=21 November 2019|date=21 November 2019|publisher=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Affaire Alaa Abou Fakher: Le procureur militaire inculpe 2 militaires|url=https://libnanews.com/affaire-alaa-abou-fakher-le-procureur-militaire-inculpe-2-militaires/|date=21 November 2019|access-date=22 November 2019|publisher=Libnanews}}</ref>\n\n== Analysis and reactions ==\n[[File:DebateTent BeirutMadinati 24Nov2019.jpg|thumb|Debate tent in Beirut's Martyr's Square discussing economic policy, hosted by Beirut Madinati.]]\nIn contrast to the 2005 [[Cedar Revolution]], in which support for the main sides of the political conflict were aligned with political parties and the [[Sunni]]\u2013[[Shiite]] Muslim sociological and religious divide in Lebanon, the [[2015\u201316 Lebanese protests]] started to include criticism of leaders within the anti-Hezbollah community. The 2019 protests bypassed this sociological divide further, as they were part of a genuine grassroots movement that has not been directed by any political party, cross-sectarian in a broader sense than those of 2015 and taking place across Lebanon, rather than only in Beirut. The protests are an existential threat to the Lebanese government and political elite and a revolution. The 2019 society-wide nature of the protests has its seed in the 2015\u20132016 protests.<ref name=\"AJE_social_revn\">{{cite news | last1= Khatib | first1= Lina | last2= | first2= | pages= | language= | title= Lebanon is experiencing a social revolution |trans-title= | date= 20 October 2019 | newspaper= [[Al Jazeera English]] | url= https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/lebanon-experiencing-social-revolution-191020065959490.html |access-date=20 October 2019 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20191020135322/https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/lebanon-experiencing-social-revolution-191020065959490.html |archivedate= 20 October 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== International reactions ===\n[[File:Zbeeb Fransabank Beirut 28Nov2019.jpg|thumb|Investigative journalist [[Mohammad Zbeeb]] gives a talk about his reporting about public sector corruption. [[Beirut]], 28 November 2019.]]\n* U.S. Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] \u2013 \"I support the Lebanese people protesting and demanding their government take care of all of its people, not just the rich and powerful.\"<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=ewarren |number=1186357501329104899 |date=21 October 2019|title=I support the Lebanese people protesting and demanding their government take care of all of its people, not just the rich and powerful. As we fight corruption in our home, we should support those fighting corruption in theirs.}}</ref>\n* U.S. Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] \u2013 \"The Arab Spring rose up to fight corruption, repression, inequality and austerity. The Lebanon and Iraq protests show this spirit is still very much alive.\"<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=SenSanders |number=1186762286507220994 |date=22 October 2019|title=The Arab Spring rose up to fight corruption, repression, inequality and austerity. The Lebanon and Iraq protests show this spirit is still very much alive. If we want a progressive future, we need to build up a global movement of and for working people.}}</ref>\n* Iranian Supreme Leader [[Ali Khamenei]] \u2013 \"The people have justifiable demands, but they should know their demands can only be fulfilled within the legal structure and framework of their country.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-30/khamenei-signals-iran-opposition-to-uprisings-in-lebanon-iraq|title=Khamenei Signals Iran Opposition to Uprisings in Lebanon, Iraq|first1=Alaa|last1=Chahine|date=30 October 2019|access-date=29 November 2019|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref>\n* Spokesperson for [[Global Affairs Canada]] Barbara Harvey \u2013 \"Canada calls on all Lebanese parties and leaders to reject violence and encourage a peaceful and timely transition to a new government, which respects and responds to the will of the Lebanese people.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rcinet.ca/en/2019/11/04/canada-urges-timely-and-peaceful-transition-amid-lebanon-protests/|title=Canada urges 'timely and peaceful transition' amid Lebanon protests|author=Levon Sevunts|date=4 November 2019|website=RCI {{!}} Radio Canada International|language=en|access-date=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n* French Foreign Minister [[Jean-Yves Le Drian]] \u2013 \"Prime Minister Hariri resigned a few moments ago, which in a way makes the crisis even more serious. [...] Lebanon\u2019s stability depends on willingness to listen to people and their demands.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uk.ambafrance.org/Lebanon-s-stability-depends-on-willingness-to-listen-to-people-and-their|author=Jean-Yves Le Drian|date=31 October 2019|title=Lebanon's stability depends on willingness to listen to people and their demands|website=AmbaFrance|language=en|access-date=13 November 2019}}</ref>\n* U.S. Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] \u2013 \"The Iraqi and Lebanese people want their countries back. They are discovering that the Iranian regime\u2019s top export is corruption, badly disguised as revolution. Iraq and Lebanon deserve to set their own courses free from [[Ali Khamenei|Khamenei]]'s meddling.\"<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=SecPompeo |number=1191844279674712064 |date=5 November 2019|title=The Iraqi and Lebanese people want their countries back. They are discovering that the Iranian regime\u2019s top export is corruption, badly disguised as revolution. Iraq and Lebanon deserve to set their own courses free from @khamenei_ir's meddling.}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|2019 Lebanese protests}}\n* [[2015\u201316 Lebanese protests]]\n* [[Politics of Lebanon]]\n* [[2019 Chilean protests]] for similar protests\n* [[2019 Iraqi protests]] for similar protests\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ongoing protests}}{{Portal bar|Lebanon|Politics}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lebanese protests, 2019-20}}\n[[Category:2018\u20132020 Arab protests]]\n[[Category:2019 in Beirut]]\n[[Category:2019 protests]]\n[[Category:2020 in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Intifadas]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:November 2019 events in Lebanon|Protests]]\n[[Category:October 2019 events in Lebanon|Protests]]\n[[Category:Ongoing protests]]\n[[Category:Politics of Lebanon|2019 protests]]\n[[Category:Protests in Lebanon|2019-20]]\n", "name_user": "Ahmadassi03", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_Lebanese_protests"}
